column6: To Boot New York Men's Scott Boot
column13: Very simple, very elegant, and very comfortable
column14: Following the tradition of To Boot, the Scott is  very well made.  The leather is supple, and while showing imperfections, these do not detract from the appearance but add a flavour of originality.  One of the major attractions of the boot is its restrained character: there is no ornamentation, no fancy stitching, but plain simplicity of the front which, when polished to high lustre, makes the boot perfect for wearing  both with a formal navy or black suit as much as with a pair of khakis.  The elegance of the boot is amplified by the tall, quite narrow shaft that follows the contour of the lower calf and vanishes high up  within the trouser leg: a superb way of eliminating the wearer's fear that the hem of the latter will get stuck on the top of the shaft, which is a common occurrence with ankle-long shafts.  Thee narrowness of the shaft does not impair the ease of donning the boot at all: the full length zipper is placed in a manner that facilitates pulling the boot on.  Originally, I feared the shaft will be the reason for return: I had a major foot surgery recently and ended up with a fairly restricted mobility of the ankle joint.  It seemed I will not be able to put my foot inside the boot.  To my amazement - although with the help of a longish steel shoe horn - the foot went in without any difficulties.  Once there, the boot felt like a very comfortable medical device that supports and holds the foot firmly in place, assisting in walking rather than impeding it!  Thus, even under these somewhat taxing circumstances, the boots proved to be very comfortable, and a great pleasure to wear. Please, note that the boot is not meant to be used roughly.  It IS a dress boot: a simple one, but also one that is very elegant even if its shape is somewhat old--fashioned (Amazon's photograph does not do it full justice). Hence,  it will require both sensible use and maintenance: avoid "lumberjacking"  while wearing these boots, apply high quality polish frequently (due to the high quality of leather, high gloss is quite easily attainable), and a set of cedar shoe trees ready to use after each wearing, and you will have a splendid addition to your "manly wardrobe"  that will last several years.

column14:
[[VIDEOID:8247d3e61c8d5a6d8e35de39bc10f75f]] Designer look with a subtle edge.

Do you like Sugar Skulls? Do you have a bit of rebel in you, but love on-trend fashion?

This vegan handbag is structured but still butter soft.
Covered in button 'pillows', you certainly won't see this bag around every corner. Gold accents and gold slides cover the handle.
Look closely at the slides. They are SUGAR SKULLS!

Also known as calaveras, the sugar skull icon is growing in popularity. Mixed with an upscale looking handbag, it just makes you smile.

The bag itself is very well made. There is a top zipper as well as a side zip with a soft touchable tassel.
If you like the unusual, this beautiful bag is for you.

column13: I bought the green Superfeet insoles, size C. ...
column14: I bought the green Superfeet insoles, size C. I had to trim a little to fit in my shoes, and because they do take up room, they only really worked with my more loose-fitting shoes. When I first put them on, I was surprised that they weren't soft. I wore them just a couple of hours the first day, and then a few hours the next and gradually increased to all day. I now keep these in my work shoes & am so thankful for them. I am a nurse & often work 12+ hours shifts. I have high arches & used to change into different shoes every few hours to try and relieve foot fatigue and aches. I was forever wishing I could just kick off my shoes, because I couldn't stand wearing them anymore. My co-workers didn't appear to suffer quite as much as me, but I still thought my troubles were purely down to my work/long hours. Now, I can wear the same pair of shoes for the entire shift & I no longer have that tired feeling. For me, these insoles are a blessing.

column6: Easy Street Women's Khanni
column13: I have the worst trouble finding shoes that fit my narrow feet and ...
column14: I have the worst trouble finding shoes that fit my narrow feet and don't rub my heels. I have found after years of painful shoes that slingbacks are the way to go. This shoe is the only shoe I've found in YEARS that hasn't killed my feet. I am often required to walk over a mile uphill each week in heels, and with any other shoe, I can't walk 50 feet without being reduced to walking barefoot with raw heels, even with moleskin over heel grips, and nylons over bandaids. With these shoes, I can walk around with no problems, and have completely worn down two and a half pairs. That being said, there is a difference between 2A and N (and even 2N). 2A is much narrower, but luckily the first time I wore my newest pair, I was walking around in the rain for a couple of hours (boohoo!), so they stretched out fairly well. Overall, a blessing in the disguise of a shoe. I wish they were still being made.

column6: Asics Gel Resolution 6 WIDE Women's Tennis Shoe White/Silver - WIDE version
column14:
I wear these for 1-3 hours at a time on a hard court surface. Just like other reviewers have said, they fit large (I went down a half size) and have a lot of room in the toe.

The toe box ran a bit narrow for a C/D Width shoe but they still fit.

I have plantar fasciitis and wear custom orthotics in my running shoes. I don't like wearing orthotics with tennis shoes since doing so tends to over correct the problem and I end up with an almost twisted ankle.

These shoes are great for stability and absorb impact well. I've recently tried Nike, New Balance and a non-stabilized Asics tennis shoes and these are by far the best.

I wore these out of the box with no break in time and they are great. They also provide excellent control on the court.

column13: Superfeet Yellow Not Super for Me
column14:
Was hopeful with this product. I have fairly flat feet and was looking for improved support in my hockey skates. The reviews online I read seemed mixed but with their guarantee I decided to give the Superfeet Yellow insoles a try.

The Superfeet insoles are simple to use, just sized using footbed from my skates and then slipped into the skate. Initially I was pleased with the result. Felt my heal was secure in the slightly raised position the insole creates and my blades were even on the ice. I liked that raised positioning especially when skating backwards.

The negative for me was in the knee. After using the insoles for @ 5 sessions I began to get knee discomfort that I did not have previously. Skated a couple more times in the Superfeet but discomfort continued. Removed the Superfeet and went back to the original insoles. Pain went away and has not returned. But the Superfeet have been....

column6: Damero Women's Vintage Leather Shoulder Bag
column14:
So far so good. I've been looking for an inexpensive tote bag and tried a "vegan leather" version but just couldn't get over the plastic feel and smell, so I went on the hunt for a deal on a simple leather tote. I prefer the unfinished look, but wasn't looking to spend $100-$200 on a Madewell or Baggu leather tote just yet. That's when I found this bag.

Besides having the exact look and feel I was going for, it also included an organizer. Since most of the bags in this unfinished and simple style lack anything more than a small zippered pouch inside, I had pretty much decided I would need to buy an organizer on my own at some point. This bag just worked that problem out for me. I don't need a lot of pockets, just someplace to put my phone where it's easily accessible and a pocket for my pepper spray and pocket knife. Everything else I keep in smaller bags. All my stuff fits nicely in this bag and it's half the weight of the Madewell satchel I've been carrying, so my neck and back are already thanking me.

The leather seems to be nice quality and it definitely smells and moves like top-notch leather. I purchased the coffee color because I generally wear all black and I love the way this color looks with that aesthetic. The color is true to the photo so there were no surprises there. The strap drop length is just fine and about average for this type of bag (~9.25"). I do think the bag is smaller than what the product description says, though. I measure it to be about 16" wide, 10.5" tall, and 4.5" deep. I guess if you take out the little piece at the bottom of the purse that keeps it structured you add another few inches to the height, but overall the dimensions on Amazon are incorrect. I would have preferred to receive a bag closer to the size in this item's description, but I find the actual size to be manageable as well so I'll keep the bag. The seller should definitely correct the dimensions in the description, though.

I will report back if there are any issues, but overall I'm very satisfied with the bag. I may even come back for a black version as well. Time will tell. I really would like a larger tote, though, so maybe I'll look out for when this brand creates a larger size.

*Note: The below photos were taken under somewhat harsh lighting. The leather isn't *quite* as shiny as it appears in the photos. It's a nice pebbled leather with some gloss. Nothing too polished.br />
I will report back if there are any issues, but overall I'm very satisfied with the bag. I may even come back for a black version as well. Time will tell. I really would like a larger tote, though, so maybe I'll look out for when this brand creates a larger size.

column6: Lauren Ralph Lauren Women's Latrice Wedge Sandal
column13: So cute, but so painful you can't walk in them without bleeding.
column14: I wanted to love these shoes. When you first put them on, the inside is so soft, you'll think they're going to be your dream shoe. You walk around your house few a few minutes, they still seem great, so you grab your bag and head out. That's when it all goes wrong. I live in New York, so I do a good deal of walking. I know not every shoe is comfortable at first, but this morning, I hadn't made it two blocks before I looked down and realized my toes were BLEEDING from the strap across them cutting in. I had to stop, pull out my emergency bandaids so I didn't bleed all over my shoes, then hobble back home. Again, this was after two blocks. The strange part is, the shoes aren't even tight. If anything, I'd say the lean on the wide side, so I was shocked that the straps could dig in this way. These shoes are super cute, and if you try them on, you'll want them. But if you walk any distance as part of your day (ie more than a block), don't do it. Shoes you can't walk in, no matter how cute, simply aren't worth it.

column6: Corso Como Women's Mystic Mary Jane Flat
column13: Very cute and well padded on the foot bed!!!
column14:
After reading some of the reviews about this shoes I was worried about ordering them. I'm soooo glad I ordered them anyway. I ordered my normal size 6. Fits perfectly. (I sometimes have to go up a half size in a flat and down a half size in a high heel) They are lovely shoes and look very well made. The first day I've worn them I've managed to have them on all day with no rubbing and no breaking in being necessary. As with most pointed shoes I was worried that they would pinch my toes but these shoes do not pinch at all. I can't say enough about how well padded and squishy soft the footbeds are in these shoes!!! I feel like i'm walking little clouds.
My only gripe if I can even call it a gripe is that the strap across the top of the foot is oddly long. My feet have a very high bone on top so most of the time I have problems with a mary jane strap being too tight. I would have to put these in the tightest hole for them to be snugly secure around my foot which leaves a long tab...so I just wear them on the 2nd hole to keep the tab from looking too long. It doesn't bother me that they aren't skin tight across the top of my foot. The strap is more for decoration anyway. The width of these shoes feels very medium. There is a bit of toe cleavage even at the pinky as they have a low vamp. I'm going to order them in other colors because they are a perfect shoe to wear if you have to walk around for a day. I received 3 compliments on them in one day!!! They are really beautiful little flats and I highly recommend them.

column13: I've tried at least six other brands of hiking boots and these fit me the best. When wearing shoes size 9 is the largest ...
column14: I've been hiking every morning before work for 1 to 1 1/2 hours for years. Now that I'm retired my husband and I are going to do longer hikes but my old boots cause problems (toe cramping) if I'm out for longer than two hours. I've tried at least six other brands of hiking boots and these fit me the best. When wearing shoes size 9 is the largest I wear, but for these boots, size 10 ended up fitting best.The toes on my left foot do touch when going downhill, but I have been lacing them tight around the ankle for descents and that has helped.  I've hiked as long as seven hours in these puppies and am grateful for the supportive and lightweight boot. And they look good.

column6: Women's DailyShoes Lace-Up Ankle Padded Collar Work Combat Ladies Booties
column13: These are NOT steel toe boots, they do fit well, and are comfortable and cute
column14:
Free product provided for my evaluation and review.
I received a size 11. It fit as expected.

These are NOT steel toe boots. The 'hard toe' advertised is only a bit harder than the rest of the boot, and I am sure if steel toe is required, you will get in trouble if you try wearing these. I know of a supervisor that will step on toes to see- if this toe gets stepped on, it will hurt. I can mash it down with my thumb.

These shoes are lighter than they look - each one weighs a bit less than a pound by my scales (0.912lb) which is about the same as my tennis shoes. I'm sure smaller sizes will weigh less, but I have a great big foot and often boots like this will be heavy. These are not.

Like:
- good tread, with plenty of traction on the sole
-1 inch heel that feels flat to wear
-soft cuff at the top, padded tongue
-looks really cute- great with jeans, the contrasting white stitching looks very nice
-I find them comfortable- they are a medium width that is a bit roomier than normal
-the body of the shoe seems fairly well constructed. They'd compare to shoes found at Megamart B&M or Payless stores.

Downsides
-the insole will come out when I take these off, it is not glued down. It is flat, and plain, and I'll probably replace it with something better.
-all man made materials
-not steel toe, toe is only a bit harder than the rest of the boot, NOT safe for jobs that demand steel toes
-this material is prone to wear shiny- it looks like suede, but it is man-made.

Overall, a nice looking attractive, lightweight but warm boot for school, hiking, or casual wear. Might be appropriate for many workplaces but not ones that require steel toe boots-I took a star off for that. The value for price to quality is about average, and the fit is on target. The boots are Made in China.

column6: Crocs Women's Patricia II Wedge Sandal
column14:
I love these sandals. I wasn't sure of the size so I got a 10 and an 11. The 11 was too long. The 10 is better I think a 10-1/2 would have been perfect but 10 is fine. I will say this. I have a narrow (AA) foot so I can't wear a lot of Medium width shoes.

These shoes fit like a AA. They are very narrow so if you are a true Medium, this should is not for you. The arch support is fantastic. I have plantar fasciitis and can never get a shoe with enough arch support. This rubber shoe has it all. It's actually the first time that my arches are not falling in.

I'm going to get another pair, probably black, and wear them a few days to see how they might fare on vacation in October.

column6: Birkenstock Women's Gizeh Thong Sandal
column13: Birko-Flor = Faux Leather. Not a leather upper.
column14: Birko-Flor = Faux Leather. Not a leather upper. Don't get me wrong, this is a great sandal from a fantastic shoe maker BUT I had expected the "upper" - meaning the parts of the shoe that go over the foot - to be leather. It is not. The "upper" material is listed on the box as "Birko-Flor" which appears to be fancy, German-shoemaker-speak for faux leather. Feels like vinyl on the outer-facing side; feels like polyester felt or faux wool on the inside that comes into contact with your foot. Very comfortable, but am wondering how the faux leather is going to hold up over time. The footbed-liner - meaning the part of the foot your foot sits on - is actually leather. A final note about the color: "Graceful Toffee" is a glossy, metallic brown. It looks like glossy mid-value brown indoors, but outside, in the sunlight, it looks more metallic, like a warm bronze. Very pretty, but did I mention it's not leather??

column13: but I'm glad I went with the 8 since the shoe is ...
column14: Review is for the "natural" colour. The star rating is for the actual look and fit of the shoe, not for the seller.  I'm a size 7.5 to 8, but I'm glad I went with the 8 since the shoe is somewhat on the narrow side in the toe area. Lengthwise, there is some space in the front even though I had to attach those soft heel backs since I blistered after wearing them for just 20 mins, both heels.  The shape of the shoe is really nice and looks great with drapey pants, skirts, and jeans. Can be dressed up or down which makes it a very versatile pair of shoes.  My only complaint is that the pattern looks a little different on both shoes, but I think (to an extent) that's just part of the material. It's not super noticeable, but one of the shoes does have more prominent white spots on the vamp. The left shoe actually looked damaged on closer inspection, but I covered the scuffs with a permanent marker. Couldn't complain too much because of the price. The price was good and I had already worn them out in a rush before I realized so I'm stuck with them, but I'm kind of glad I didn't get to return them because the look of the shoes is great.  Also, the pattern didn't have the zig zag-ish look. It's just more of a spotted look.  Overall  - great versatile shoe -slightly on the narrow side, but great lengthwise - shoemetro (seller) should inspect their stock more closely before shipping. If I had paid more, I would've been very disappointed. But I made do with a permanent marker

column13: Love this bag; its so versatile!
column14:
I have had so many bags since I have had children. I have gone through baby bags and so many Vera Bradley bags I could choke a horse. I have not had a LeSportsac purse before just a computer bag. But the computer bag has lasted me years so I thought I am going to give a handbag a shot.

I can easily still put a pull up and wipes in one section and no one is the wiser!

I can take all sorts of things in the bag from cosmetics, wallet, iPhone, keys, papers, diapers, etc. Its easy to clean if something gets on it too!

I highly suggest and will be purchasing others in other colors/designs.

column13: Probably won't handle a full size firearm
column14: My husband bought this purse for me because he got tired of my complaining about trying to carry in a "regular" purse. First off this purse is so darn cute and seems to have a decent amount of room for most of the stuff I carry. Be aware the concealed carry pocket barely accommodates my Springfield XDM9 with 13 round magazine (extended magazine - 19 rounds will not fit). This is a medium length barrel gun and it's kind of a tight fit, This purse will probably not hold a full length gun.  My Ruger LCR fits just fine, so if you carry a compact or sub-compact firearm you should be OK. If you carry a full size this might not be  the purse for you. He also bought me another purse (slightly more subdued - black and white instead of hot pink) from amazon that has a diagonal zipper for the concealed carry pocket and this type handles the Springfield with the extended magazine just fine, and will most likely accommodate a full size gun. Good luck!

column6: Birkenstock Unisex Birko Sport Arch Support - Sport
column14:
In the past 5 years I have most likely spent about $300 on arch supports. Yes, I have flat feet. I got these today and they appear to work rather well. Much better than 90% of the ones I have tossed out or are in my drawer waiting to be tossed out. As an amateur expert on these things let me suggest a few ideas.
I prefer full shoe inserts. The half ones have a certain logic in terms of giving your toes more room, but the ball of your foot and inner pad also need support. These are the full length. These are unusual to me because they have a hard bottom shape and a soft rubber top. They seem awkward at first, but after wearing them most of the day I noticed a real sense of support in a pair of basketball shoes.

If you are still with me I have some buying suggestions. Look at the shoes you plan to put these into and use the euro number - not the American size. Your shoes may have a range so pick something in the middle. Buy the one that best describes your foot - high arch, normal or flat. Here is the "secret". This insert will fill up the shoe or sneaker near the toes and push the foot up into the top of the shoe. Most of them do this. Don't wear inserts with jammed up feet. Next: if you don't have shoes that handle full inserts go to a discount store with name brands at a discount. This is what I do. Take the inserts with you. Tell the clerk. Now, start trying on different designs without and with the insert. Find the design and size that allows room for your toes and the top of your foot. Cramming your feet into a shoe is never a wise thing.

I got lucky and found a pair of gray basketball sneakers that accommodated the insert and my foot! Gees! What a difference. I have a pair of boots with high toe room, but I could not remove the glued insert in the boot. No good. Another pair of basketball shoes also did not work. But, the ones that worked did allow me to remove their insert and replace it with this one. Voila! I have a most comfortable pair of shoes.

Over the years I have visited a podiatrist twice - completely useless visits. He would recommend some sort of happy feet stuff or other. He was useless. Experiment around. I will say that I have been wrong to expect too much. It is critical to be picky about having reasonable comfort. In my experience if the shoe feels comfortable in the store, it will work. I hate it when someone says, "Oh, those will stretch." Naaa!

Yes, you may have to compromise on style and color. The objective is to have comfortable feet. If you do have foot problems I have had great help from exercise. Hold onto 10 lbs and hang your heals out over a board or step. then raise and lower yourself on the balls of your feet. This has certainly helped my balance and walking. There is no free lunch. Compromise. If your feet are not comfortable, keep working at it. One of the most ugly pair of cross trainer sneakers I owned had the best darn arch support. comfort wise they were great. Hardly fashionable looking. No, I did not wear them with a tuxedo. For working out they were awesome until they completely rotted out. Nike stopped making them!!!! so much for great design and lousy look.

Hope this helps.

A Week Later - Fantastic. The soles have settled into my basketball work out sneakers and my feet are far more comfortable. I have great stability. My plan is to follow my own directions above and get another pair of sneakers. These supports really work for me.e. Voila! I have a most comfortable pair of shoes.

column6: Topo Athletic Runduro Road Running Shoe - Men's
column13: It's been a great experience to have a pair of shoes that feels ...
column14:
At this point I have put in 350 miles in Runduros. It's been a great experience to have a pair of shoes that feels like it has just right balance between stability and minimalism.
These felt great out of the box, the B.O.A. system is fine, if you are looking for a shoelace feel, stop it. This is a different system and it has its own feel and its tendency is to hug the top of your feet, which works great in terms of leaving plenty of room and feel in the toe box.
Most of the miles I've put in my Runduros were on pavement but there were plenty of instances where I used them on trails and the performance was just fine. I have a pair of trail running shoes that I use for long trail runs but the Runduros are great to use on days that I mix both or just on the road.
At this point I have clear signs of wear on the soles, they are beginning to feel a bit muted but I think I can probably get close to 500 miles on them (mind you I run at an average cadence of 180-185 which is supposed to help with longevity).
What would I change in these?
I'm not sure...I really like them and will get a second pair in a few months. I suppose that it would be interesting to know what a lower stack height and slightly softer compound on the sole would do...Although I'd rather try that on a different model as opposed to changing the Runduros and a formula that does what it's supposed to do

column6: Oakley Men's LSA Water Boot
column13: Great Water Boot for the BWCA
column14: These boots were purchased for a 2 week long camping/canoeing trip in the Boundary Waters Canoe Area and were worn both in the water and while portaging up to about 3/4 mile across dry land. In addition, a few shorter trail hikes were taken while wearing these boots. They provided good support but, more importantly, drained and dried quickly. The boots were not broken in before the trip but, luckily, did not cause any rubbing or blisters, provided good arch support, and were comfortable for the entire time. Of course, the wearer does need to be sure to lace these up properly -- they are not meant to be the kind of shoe that slips on and off.  While these were used on some shorter trail hikes, I would not recommend them solely as a hiking boot. The sole is soft and more flexible than a normal hiking boot. After only about 10 days of not-too-intense use, the rocks have taken a fair number of small bites out of the tread on the bottom of the boot. The tops of the boot are fairly soft and do not provide much toe protection (flexible like the top of an athletic shoe). This flexibility is good in a water boot for walking and balancing on uneven wet surfaces, but was not as welcome on trail hikes. If you have a sore or stubbed toe, you will probably feel like you've re-stubbed it several more times during your trail hike.  I'm giving this 5 stars because it will likely be the Go-To water boot and functioned well for its intended purpose.

column6: Nike Men's Air Max TR180 Cross Trainer
column13: An Excellent Shoe, with One Tiny Quirk
column14:
This is a great shoe and does what I need it to do. I stand on my feet all day at work and wanted something that would keep my feet comfortable. These shoes provide great cushion, giving your heel a very soft spot to land on. The top portion of the shoe has a thin mesh, which provides good air flow. The only thing that is incredibly odd is that they stick to concrete!

I've looked at other reviews and it seems like no one else has mentioned this issue, but the threads of the sole somehow dig into the concrete, causing a velcro-ripping sound with each step. It feels like walking on velcro. I don't understand how that's possible, but it is. Luckily, concrete seems to be the only surface that has this effect. On the bright side, it does provide excellent traction.

But velcro-effect aside, the shoe is incredibly comfortably, which is what really matters to me, so I'll still give it the five stars.

column6: Salt Water Sandals by Hoy Shoe The Original Sandal
column13: Best durable summer sandals; just like they were when I was a kid
column14:
I grew up wearing salt water sandals and remember my mom loving them for their flexibility, the ease of cleaning them and how fast they dry off. I used to go to the rocky beaches of Seattle all the time in them and I smile when I remember those days in the sandals.
When I was in the market for sandals for my daughter I was so excited to see that they still made them and wow so many colors! We have them in gold, white and black just for the flexibility of matching them to outfits. My 6 year old loves them and has asked for more in purple and pink.

They are still as durable as I remember. These are not the type you would ever go climbing in, they don't have a great grippy sole, but she has no problem climbing things with them on. They are 100% leather and top quality. We also purchased a more sturdy pair of hiking type of sandals for her and funny those lasted 2 months. But her salt water have withheld the test of time this summer.

As long as she wears them next year I will be ordering them again, they are wonderful sandals!

column6: VertX Men's Polarized Sunglasses Sport Cycling Running w/ free Microfiber Pouch
column13: I was extremely satisfied with these sunglasses
column14:
This review will go through my entire experience with these glasses.
Day 1 - 5/5
At this price point, I was extremely satisfied with these sunglasses. Soft rubber nose piece and arm tips were very comfortable. Even after extended wearing the rubber was able to move with my head and big ears preventing a glasses induced headache. The lenses are indeed polarized, not top quality however that's not what you are paying for here. The style is also pretty sweet, I have a fairly large wide head. Most glasses look too small on my face and squeeze the sides of my head, these do not. They also fit my wife and she has a smaller, normal sized head.
Day 2 - 3/5
The left nose piece started coming off the frame. They are held on with two tabs, and one slipped out of the frame. After pushing it back in 2 dozen times I came to the super glue solution, but never got around to the fix. This isn't too bad because I don't mind a little diy fix, but for a brand new pair of shades is unacceptable.
Day 3 - 1/5
The frames broke under one of the lenses. I was shocked, taking them off my head and seeing the plastic had separated. Also bummed out, even with the rubber nose piece falling off these are still the most comfortable 20 dollar sunglasses I've ever worn. They had only seen 3 days of what I'll classify as light-normal use. I wore them on my face to sit around a pool, wash cars, etc... nothing too crazy. I don't bang my face onto anything, they never fell off, and went straight into a hard case when not in use. The only explanation I can come up with is maybe they don't like the heat (it was around 112 in the day) and it caused them to self destruct. I hope this isn't the case because I'm still contemplating ordering another pair and hoping the first was defective.

Bottom line: At this price point they would be a slam dunk if they had stayed together. Comfort, polarized lens, and style are all the best Ive found for 20 dollars. Unfortunately, mine fell apart. After reading other reviews I may have a defective product. Unless I decide to buy another pair and they produce better results, I cannot give my recommendation for this product.

column13: Not what I expected from Magnum
column14:
Duty- security: medium to slight heavy use.
Not what I expected from Magnum. I have had several different boots from different brands. I've had 2 pairs from Magnum and this was my third, it is by far the worst pair I have owned.
These boots fit a bit larger than the real size that is marked. I considered returning them because I felt they were too loose around my feet.
I decided to give them a try anyway.
I have only had them 2 months and there is noticeable wear on the bottom sole both front and back.
There is nothing to help with tying the laces. No lace locks of any kind, causing the boots to become loose after a few steps. The laces themselves are starting to get tears on them.
The worst thing of all is that these boots do not breathe! I work a 4-8 hrs shifts and when I get home my socks are soaked! It makes my feet sweat too much.
Seriously considering replacing them after only 2 months.

column14: I couldn't wait to get these glasses in because in the pictures they looked really cute and a I love Coleman products. I have a stigmatism in my eyes, so I really need a dark pair of polarized glasses to keep me from squinting and my eyes watering all of the time when I am in the sun. This is a must because I am an outdoorsy kind of girl. These glasses, which I purchased in black and are adorable, they fit my face perfect and they are so light that they do not leave a mark on my nose like most glasses do...and did I mention I look great in them? (Just joking...but I really do like how they look and feel) another great feature that I like and has held up so far...the frames have not stretched when I put them over the top of my big head when entering a store. So when I read that in the description of these glasses that is what prompted me to make the purchase! So many of my glasses have been donated or given to a friend for that exact reason. I recommend these glasses as they are gorgeous and durable.  I received these glasses at a discounted price in exchange for an honest review and like I said these are durable and should last a while as long as your not one of those people that can't keep up with glasses and lose them all of the time.

column13: Simple and fun to wear. Fit true to size (for wide feet person).
column14: I like these sneakers, they fit true to size (for wide-feet individual). They are simple and fun to wear, yet have interesting twists. I got 2 pairs--one pair in black with snake sprint, silver coating and silver-tone metal mesh on the tongue, and one pair in gold with khaki-like texture upper and snake print, gold coating and gold-tone metal mesh on the tongue. The reason I gave them 4 stars was because, in my opinion, the craftsmanship was OK for me. As you can see in one of my photos, the insole lining does not fit the insole totally, so you could see the stitches exposed. For the fit, for someone who have wide feet like I do, I'd suggest to go with your true sneakers size or 1/2 size down; if you have narrow and slender feet, I'd suggest to go at least 1 size down. For examples, my 6.5M-size shoes (width: 3.25"; length: 9-3/8") fit me very well and I usually wear sneakers in 7.5M-9M (depending on brands).

column13: The men's versions always get the good neutral colors
column14: I'm taking off one star for the abysmal color options. The men's versions always get the good neutral colors. I know that this is one of the older styles but the colors don't get any better. I love this shoe. I have been wearing The One for running and after a year or so, I've compacted the soles. It's a good inch thinner now. It still works well but as I'm picking up more miles, I wanted something with more cushion. I run on pavement. This particular style is a good size and a half smaller than let's say The One and the Torin style. I first ordered in my usual size in Altra which is half a size larger than my conventional shoe size. My toes were basically pushing out of shoes. So I ordered a 5.5 first which usually fits like a 5. But it was way too small. I opted to try the 6.5 as it's the only other size left. And I'm so happy they fit! I've seen the newer versions of this shoe and it's no longer as wide. I really need the shoes to be wider as I really like having my toes splay.

column6: Georgia Men's Composite Toe Low Heel Logger Boots
column13: but so far so good. I am a land surveyor and am always ...
column14:
I have only had these boots for a couple months, but so far so good. I am a land surveyor and am always on my feet, wlaking/trekking through all types of terrain. Whether it be concrete, dirt, or brushy hillsides, the aggressive vibram sole and very cushy insole keep my feet comfortable. They don't get hot, even in triple digit weather, walking in asphalt. Despite the composite toe, they are a bit heavy.

The only advice I have is to not pull the laces too tight through the lowest hooks as this pinches my feet and irritates them; however doing so with the remaining upper 2 pairs of hooks is fine. I found thst doing this makes for the best fit of the boot.

For the extremely competitive price, it'd be bery difficult to find a Gore-Tex lined, Vibram sole, composite safety toe, memory foam/extra cushioned heel insole boot anywhere. Given, the price reflects a boot made in China rather than the US. We'll see how the boot holds up after a year or so.

They are much bigger and wider than any other sandal I've tried so far, but that isn't a good thing for sandals since you want them to fit enough to not slip around when walking to avoid blisters and protect your feet.

column6: Reebok Women's Princess Sneaker
column14:
No longer good!
I thought I was going crazy, because I had been wearing these shoes for years and years and loved them, always had a pair or sometimes two handy for when the old pair's life was ending, and suddenly the same size didn't fit at all and my feet got extremely smelly and sweaty while wearing them. My old pair still fit and so did other shoes, so it had to be the shoes. But reading these reviews I know that it isn't me... Do not buy these shoes! Bad about this website: I was just chatting with an employee to ask about this issue before reading theses reviews and he told me that nothing changed when I literally asked about it. So that is no way to treat a customer, it's basically a lie... They should be honest about this change, they cheapened the production, making this a bad shoe, not what you could get before.
To top it off, I sent in this review at the Reebok website before and it was turned down for not meeting their standards. I checked, nope, it's up to standard alright. I guess Reebok is not into honest criticism? So submitting this review to amazon and other places now, I mean I took the time to write it...

column13: I absolutely love it. I usually wear a 9-9 1/2 depending ...
column14:
This is the first lifting sneaker I have purchased. It has changed by world! I absolutely love it. I usually wear a 9-9 1/2 depending on the sneaker/brand and after reading the reviews I decided to go with the 9 1/2. I'm glad I did becuase it fits perfectly (borderline snug - but I think the 10 would have been to large). I also have a wider foot, so I was nervous about that after reading some reviews saying that the sneaker was narrow, but the width was perfect!

After the first time wearing them I noticed a big difference in the balance I had for lunges, pistols, split squats, etc. They are light-weight, comfortable and I absolutely love the colors. I would buy a pair in the blue if they had a pair left in my size. Highly recommended for any weight training, strength training - but I wouldn't recommend to wear for running.

column13: Had to return them, too wide and heavy
column14:
These shoes were reasonably comfortable and fit like other 10.5 shoes I've purchased, but I had to return them for 2 reasons.

First off they're too wide. I have narrow feet and these shoes leave a sizable gap on either side of my feet, making for a sloppy look. Second, these shoes are really heavy because the entire white bottom section seems to be pure rubber. The combination of the wide fit and heaviness make these constantly flop on my feet while walking so I couldn't keep them.

They were comfortable otherwise and looked really cool in person, so if you have wider feet they may work for you.

column6: Vionic Bryce Sandals with Orthaheel Technology
column13: Warning: Don't Leave Them In The Sun!
column14:
You would think if you purchased a sandal you could take them to the pool, the lake, or maybe to the beach, slip them off for some fun in the sun. But you cant! When I left them in the sun the heal cup shrunk about 1/4" around the outside. Now the sandals are uncomfortable to wear and I have to toss them. I contact Orthaheel/Vionicshoes about my issue and they told me the sandals have a 6mo warranty too bad. My pair was about 1 year old but not heavy warn. column6: Madden Girl Women's Darrlin Dress Sandal
column14:
I liked these shoes as something to wear to work, and I work in an office so I'm not walking around in them all day. They're ok as far as comfort goes, nothing special there.

The one thing that I really didn't like is that the strap over the toe actually wraps under the minimal padding of the sole. Not a big deal at first, until I wore them on vacation where I was walking all day long. Because the sole of the shoe is a little slippery my feet slid back and forth, which isn't uncommon in heels and not a huge bother, but with the strap underneath the padding you can feel it. My foot was rubbing on the little bump it causes constantly and I ended up with surprisingly large blisters. I don't think it's very common for a strap to wrap all the way underneath the padding, at least none of my other shoes are like that, and since the "padding" is practically non-existent it ended up being a huge problem.

So I do still wear them around the office but if I know I'm going to be walking more than that I reach for another pair of shoes for sure.

column14: PLEASE READ** I had purchased a pair of these at the Sunglasses Hut and my mom had told me she found the exact ones on Amazon. I ordered these and kept the ones purchased to compare. Sitting them side by side, they are COMPLETLY different. Even the cases are different. The ones I had ordered are replicas, not real ones. Although they are very good replicas they are MANY MANY differences. Please beware of this scam and don't let yourself pay 100+$ for fake glasses. The ray ban symbol wasn't even in the same spot it was in my real glasses (I have multiple pairs) the logo in the nose piece was upside down, the blue was a different shade, the case had a different material, the clip on front of the case was more of a hard metal than a soft leather like on the original ray ban case. Please beware and refrain from purchasing fake products.

column6: olivia + joy Emma Satchel
column13: Great Purse for the Fashionably Organized
column14: This is absolutely one of the cutest purses I have ever owned. I'm not much of a purse girl (I'm really simple when it comes to purses), but I am a stickler for organization and practicality and this purse has both and is fashionably chic to boot! The purse is a really nice size (not too big and not too small), so I am able to fit all of my essentials in it (i.e., makeup case, wallet, checkbook, 8" tablet, cell phone, keys, glasses, etc.) with room to spare and everything is not a big jumbled mess inside thanks to all of the handy pockets. There is a front zipper pocket that actually "locks" shut with the decorative lock shown on front, which I thought was a nice detail in design. There is also a nice size snap button pocket on the back, which allows easy access to frequently used items such as keys or ID. Inside the purse are three slip pockets (two in the front that are cell phone size and one in the back that is a little bigger than postcard size) and one zipper pocket. All of these pockets allow me to keep my other frequently used and smaller items tucked away neatly yet easy to find. The interior is lined with a nice polyester material with the Olivia & Joy logo on it and the outside is a good quality soft faux leather. I can't speak on the durability of it just yet since the purse is new, but I can say that it doesn't appear to be cheaply made. I would definitely buy this purse again at the sale price I bought it for as it is well worth it.

column6: Saucony Women's Cohesion 7 Running Shoe
column14:
I started running at the beginning of the year in my old beat up sneakers. Pretty soon my knees were killing me. My husband suggested getting some new running sneakers, and of course he was right! My knees felt better almost instantly when I started running in these sneakers. They are comfortable right out of the box and the fit was great in my regular size (8.5). I was also very happy with the price! Since I wasnt sure how long I would stick with running I didnt want to shell out a ton of money for shoes. These sneakers ended up being just right!

I like the colors - they arent too flashy, so I can wear them just about anywhere (I even wore them to work a few times). I do feel like they make my feet look kind of big, but thats not really an issue when Im out running. One thing I do think is a little strange is that if I wear bright colored socks I can see them through the mesh in the shoe. The thin mesh does keep them cool and comfortable though, so its a trade off. The shoes have held up fine so far in the months that Ive had them - Im more of a casual jogger, so Im certainly not anywhere close to running them into the ground. I expect they will last me a good while yet. When I need to replace them I wont hesitate to buy another pair of Saucony Cohesions!

column6: Fossil Mercer Top-Zip Work Bag
column14:
This is truly a quality workbag, with plenty of room to meet most peoples needs in a briefcase or on-the-go media storage travel-case. The design is spot on.... the center slot is mainly intended for your laptop, and my son's 15-inch macbook and my 14-inch HP fit in any of the 3 slots. The sizing for a cross-body bag is perfect..... and the inside pocket placements are genius! I especially like the outside pocket slot for my iPhone 6 plus, yes! it fits perfectly.

The top quality leather is thick smooth and durable which I knew would be top notch with a brand like Fossil, not disappointing in anyway..... great design, excellent stitching, zippers, brushed metal links and clasps. Such a handsome bag, which I want to preserve, so I will definitely be treating it with a leather sealer to keep the rain from spotting,discoloring it.... being in Oregon, it's only a matter of time before it'll be unavoidably rain-exposed and I know this workbag is going to last a good long time.

column6: Women's Fashion Polarized Sunglasses, Oversized and Vintage Style by Coleman
column14:
I do love the color combination in these glasses (I got yellow w/ black) and was very surprised to see that these are Colemans! (yes, Coleman as in slumber bags, coolers, tents)

The frame of the glasses is a light weight plastic, there is no metal on this except for on the hinges of the glasses. These fit really nicely, there's no pressure along the side of my head from wearing these, and the material of the hooks does not tangle in hair.

The lenses are lightly polarized, you can still clearly tell colors and I would say it's about 80% effective against glare (I still had to use my sun visor while wearing these while driving).

Overall I do like these glasses, they're a very flattering shape on the face and do nicely at minimizing glare.

I received these at a discounted rate in exchange for my honest, unbiased review.

column14: These shoes are very stylish and comfortable.  I typically wear a 6 or 6.5 in a sandal and ordered a 37, which was a half size too large.  I sent them back & am waiting on a 36 to arrive.  I love gladiator shooties, but they all seem to have a high heel that kill my feet after an hour.  The heel height on this shoe was perfect.  Very comfortable.  The leather upper was very flexible and comfortable, and the adjustable Velcro strap around the ankle helps tailor the shoe to your foot.  I agree with other reviewers who've written that the ankle strap is very roomy.  I have thick ankles (ugh!) and I had to overlap the straps quite a bit to get a proper fit.  If you have narrower ankles (lucky!) this might be tricky for you.  I ordered the grey, but the color looked more like taupe, which I preferred since it matched the color of my foot better.  The shoes had a great edgy look...not dowdy at all, even with all the comfort details built in.  They look awesome with my ankle pants and skinny pants and jeans.  Give them a try!

column13: for the price these are good, might need insole
column14: these boots look exactly as I wanted and expected. The fit on length was true to size for me, as I wear a half size and it is not always available. For the price, these are quality. They do not compare to, say boots of $100 or something, but at this price its fine. Also, the boot on my feet, from the bottom to the height at the top, was very high. It left excess space above my foot at the ankle side, even after really tight lacing. I solved that issue by putting in a thick, gel based insole which made up the room and then it fit fine. i have very thin, very flat feet. I have a collapsible arch,which means it totally flattens out upon standing and is flat footed but still flexible. if you have a high arch, it might not have as much excess space for you. This is on flatter feet this happens most. on me, the toe box was a bit wide also, which was also fixed with the insole addition. The rubber sole area feels very deep, as if the foot rests within it a bit. This is ok by me, but some dislike that and like them flat  across. This boot has no arch support anyhow, so if high arched, you may want an insert either way. If I had ordered a half size or size down to make this less wide, it wouldve become too short however. someone with wider or taller feet will fit this ok. the color is as expected. The soles are sythetic and rubbery. I am sure this boot will not hold up through harsh winter in which I live, nor last years, but then, its cheap. I usually spend hundreds on boots for winter. i got these for Halloween, and to then wear out after, until I can afford some silver Docs. These are really decent boots for under &20.

column14:

I have to wear a orthotics on my normal flat shoes or running shoes without no support.

Shoe runs very narrow, very narrow. The toe area you will struggle with if you are wider than average. Just go with the nike romaleos if you are wide. I usually struggle to fit in narrow shoes although when i tried them on it just puffed up the sides to fit me.
Feel nice and firm, like a glove.. Just how it's suppose to be!
Sizing runs true to size, if you wear a normal 9.5 , get a 9.5 for these.
A lot of reviews are saying go up half a size, or go down half a size. So weird i just got the same normal size as 9.5
When i received the box from fedex i felt very happy, very very happy.
some things that concerned me was the shoe box was smashed up on the sides

column6: Nike Shox R4 Men's Running Shoes
column13: Fake, but does it even matter?
column14:
They are fakes, 99% of all R4's on the Internet now are fakes, but the craftsmanship is so good on them it doesn't even matter nowadays. The fine stitching, logo, everything is on point. The only big difference is that the bootleg R4's being sold anywhere online will never have leather, as these don't, like the ones on Ebay don't; whereas back when Nike first sold these shoes I never ran into a pair where the main sidepanel isn't leather. The R4's are essentially a discontinued line so these bootlegs are the only way to get them now. If you go check any of the Chinese trading sites (like d****e.com - redacted) and search for R4's you will see merchants selling bootlegs for $60 in the exact same batch of colors and exact sizes (7-12) that the people on Ebay and Amazon are selling their R4's in. Coincidence? I will say this - it's obvious someone in China got their hands on the molds for these shoes and setup a factory with professional shoe equipment to pump these out without authorization from Nike. They might not be up to Nike's quality control standards, but these knockoffs are so good I bet the quality on these things would beat a lot of other real shoe companys' shoes.

As I said, the R4's are discontinued. Nike will re-release a couple colors now and then and places like Footlocker will carry them, but there's no rhyme or reason to it. If the knockoffs are as durable as the real thing, you have to ask yourself if it really matters that is a knockoff.

column6: TOMS Women's Classics Flat
column13: If it's good enough for Jessica Alba, it's good enough for you!
column14: These are AWESOME shoes. I own a lot of TOMS (24+ pairs and counting, including glitter Toms in just about every color it was made), but these are my go-to shoes for every day wear. They match with everything, and they instantly class up your outfit. Don't be afraid that they are so sparkly. They are glittery, but not tacky. Seriously, even Jessica Alba has a pair! (just google "Glitter Toms Jessica Alba") You can't go wrong with that.  One thing I would suggest is to not size down a complete size when buying glitter TOMS. Unlike classic fabric TOMS, the glitter material does not stretch as much over time, so sizing down by half a size will do. Another thing to note is that TOMS shoes are notoriously not consistent in sizing. That means that you can buy 2 pairs of the exact same shoes, and one pair can be CONSIDERABLY larger than the other, even though in theory, they should both be the exact same size. In fact, I have even received TOMS where one shoe is noticeably larger than the other inside the same shoe box. This means that if you KNOW you are a size 5 in Toms, and the shoes you received are too big or too small, you may want to try another size 5 again because the pair you received may have just been "off." Luckily, Amazon has an awesome return policy, so exchanging is never a problem.  One down side to these shoes is that the glitter does eventually fall off, but it is not as noticeable on the silver color glitter as it is on other darker color glitter TOMS. This is a small trade-off for me considering how versatile these shoes are. In fact, I love them so much, I just bought a back-up pair for when my pair meets its final demise.

column13: Very Comfortable and Versatile Flip Flops
column14:
I love the Reef Ginger Flip Flops. With a decent arch and very comfortable material, I find I don't have to do much breaking in on these, and can walk or stand for long periods without getting blisters or being the least bit uncomfortable. I can wear these with the most casual outfits, but find that the look nice enough to get away with a slightly nice outfit too (borderline appropriate for work depending on the office - wouldn't wear to finer restaurants).

I replace mine every year or two, depending on how much I have worn them down. My foot is an average width woman's 7.5, so I buy the 8 (since Reef doesn't make 1/2 sizes). I find that with the 8, I have a little extra sandal at the front and back (maybe an 1/8 to 1/4 of an inch), which is perfect (big pet peeve when people have toes or heels hanging off their shoes). The sandal width works well for an average foot, but I would not recommend these for someone with a wider foot, because they may find the sides of there foot over the edges of the sandal.

column6: Saucony Men's Cohesion TR8 Trail Running Shoe
column14:
This is my second pair of Saucony athletic shoes. The first pair is no longer available so I needed to look for a comparable model online. The advantage here is that instead of buying a pair of shoos a half-size too large, as I must in a shoe store where they don't stock half-sizes, I could get the precise size I needed through Amazon. In this case, after the shoes arrived I found that the heel is higher than usual which actually makes the shoes more comfortable and tends to propel me forward as I walk. It's also more restful standing still.

The main reason I bought another pair of Saucony shoes is that the sole of the old pair lasted longer than any other athletic shoe I've every owned. The reason I needed another pair was because the inside lining of the shoe was fraying. This happens with every pair of shoes, but usually by the time the lining is wearing out, the soul of the shoes are also about finished. However, my old pair of Saucony shoes still have some life in them because the sole is still sound, with plenty of tread. They are obviously built to wear well rather then to with programed obsolescence.

3 large zippered pockets

column13: The best OCR and trail runner yet!
column14: These shoes are incredible. Fit exactly to size and are snug as they should be so they stay on your feet. Bought them for use in OCR races and I found them great for hiking also. Padding on the heel is perfect and they dry quickly. The no-tie lacing system is very effective and does not slip loose; especially with The drawcinch tucked into the toungue pocket. The best part is the tread. The two direction lugs grab everything when going up hill or down hill. I simply do not slip. This is something I have never gotten from other trail, running, or hiking footwear. As others stated, for the lugs to bite the terrain, they are softer than standard show soles. So wearing them to walk or run on streets or concrete often will prematurely wear them out. Use them as intended and they are excellent!

column13: Not right for me, but not a bad shoe
column14: I have narrow feet, no bunions, and bought a half size larger than typical (10, instead of 9.5; I do usually wear a 10 in flats) -- and I still had a lot of rubbing over my big toe on both sides, right where my skin starts to be covered by the toe of the shoe.  The length was perfect, and width was fine for me (therefore, they run somewhat narrow) but the way the shoe is made just ended up being uncomfortably tight right over the big toe.  I think they would respond to stretching - the leather is soft and supple and quite nice - but between the pale matte color (not taupe, really, more pinkish flesh-tone) and heavy leather grain appearance, they actually looked too much like... weird skin.  The leather grain just emphasized the skin-ness of them.  Caution with this color if you're pale; these would be more flattering for those with darker skin tone, for more contrast between foot and shoe.  They did seem well-made.

column6: New Balance Women's WW1069 Country Trail Running Shoe
column14: I need a shoe with a "roll bar" in them, which is hard to find in a trail / hiking shoe.  However, these are very sturdy and very comfortable.  I have to remove the insole and replace it with my orthonics, and these fit perfectly once I've done that.  I typically wear and 8.5 or 9 W, and the 9 C/D just right. I'm wearing a mid-weight hiking sock with these.  If you want to wear a thicker sock, you may need to go a half size larger.  I wouldn't be on really rocky trails with these as they aren't over the ankle, but the sole seems to be thick enough to keep you from feeling every stone on a normal, groomed trail.  Update:  Recently wore these while hiking in Arizona.  It wasn't a "groomed" trail and I had no issues with stones coming through the sole.  I did have to be careful because these are not over the ankle, but they were definitely comfortable for 3-5 miles.

Even though you are in water, your feet still take a pounding, and the rough pool bottoms can tear up your feet too.  Don't waste your time and money on cheap WalMart water shoes.  If you are going to do water aerobics, as with any sport, get the right shoe!

column13: somewhat tight but very well made and very good looking.
column14:
I wear a size 13 US. These are marked 13 US. They are more like a 12 1/2. They're a little narrow as well. I took the laces out and have been wearing them at work under my desk to break them in. So far, after 1 week, they only broke in a little. I'm going to hold onto them because I have put some weight on over the last couple yrs. If I loose weight, maybe they'll fit a little better.
I measured the sole from heal to toe and it's exactly 13 inches but the actual toe of the shoe itself (where your feet are) is a little under 13 inches. So, my toes are wedged right up to the front and my heal is pressed against the back of the shoe. I checked all my other shoes and the sole is a little over 13 and the shoe area that holds your foot is right at 13. So it shows these ARE a little shorter than all my other size 13's. But..I'll give them a try. Lets see if they loosen up.
Update: Although they never really loosened up except when I used a shoe stretcher and a ton of leather softener, they are a very solid shoe and I've gotten some compliments on them. They just run about a 1/2 size small.

column6: Spenco Siesta - Women's - Vented Orthotic Shoes
column13: I am Very Happy with These Shoes!
column14:
I have to say, I am very happy with these shoes. I love the orthopedic qualities, and found these had a stress-relieving, whole-body effect. This even lasted, once I took off the shoes.

Yet, there is nothing noticeable in wearing them, to make this happen . They just feel so natural. These shoes are light on your feet, and so soft. Once you look inside the shoe, though, you will see it's in there.

I ordered these in ice blue, which is "outside the box" for a shoe color I would normally wear. Yet, I found I love the color, too. It goes perfectly with jeans, as well as with shorts or similar summer wear. The style is casual enough, yet classy enough, too. It is well balanced for any number of occasions you might like to wear them for, or for everyday use.

The venting on the shoe works really well. In the mid-day summer heat, though I did find my feet getting a bit warm, they did not sweat. So, this was definitely a welcome effect.

On a final note, I normally wear a size nine shoe, and the size in this shoe fits me perfectly.

I would definitely recommend these shoes!

Disclosure: I received a discount in exchange for my honest review. All opinions are my own.

column6: Mizuno Men's Wave Hayate Trail Running
column13: Sized and shaped very differently from Wave Inspire
column14: I run regularly in the Mizuno Wave Inspire 11, and needed shoes for a Ragnar Trail Run. The Hayate shoes of the same marked size were significantly smaller than the Inspire: much, much narrower at the ball of the foot, and the fabric across the top was prohibitively tight for me. Mind you, I don't have particularly wide feet, but I couldn't run more than a few steps in these because it was so tight across the top when pushing off. Also, although the information I found said this was a "stability" shoe, it still had a lot of torsional flex and the footprint is very narrow. I will buy the Inspire again, but returned the Hayate: it may be a great trail racing shoe for someone, but not for me.

column6: KEEN Men's Kanyon Sandal
column14: I bought these for my husband before a beach vacation.  At first he was reluctant to wear them and thought he wouldn't wear them much at all, why did I buy them, they're not his type of shoe, etc.  But after wearing them everyday on vacation, he started to like them.  He didn't like how the sand balled up under his foot when he wore them on the beach but I reminded him that they are probably not a good choice of shoe for wearing in loose sand.  Other than that he was impressed with how they dried quickly and still looked great after getting sand and salt water on them for a couple of days and he could then wear them bike riding, walking around, etc and they still looked great and felt comfortable.  He didn't tell me of anything that was uncomfortable or rubbed him about the shoe either.  The biggest plus is that his feet felt and looked great after wearing them all week because they allow for more air circulation.  He has very sweaty feet that are usually in sneakers all day so these were very beneficial. :)

column6: Bloch Women's Issabella Ballroom Shoe
column14:
I ordered these for a salsa performance. I have wide feet and bunions that make finding ballroom shoes tough, and heard that these run wide.

I have difficult feet. They are wide, like hobbits with bunions. I got these with the intention of putting them on a shoe stretcher. I could actually squeeze my feet into these shoes without stretching them, which means they probably do run wide. I ordered my street shoe size, 6.5.

Unfortunately I have to return these shoes. I don't think there's anything wrong with them, but the sole is very stiff and impossible to point my toes in. These could be great for social dancing and beginners, but offer no forefoot flexibility. Granted, I'm not sure these were intended for anything besides social dance, so it's not necessarily a defect of the shoe.

It does look like a well made shoe, and has an awesome locking mechanism. I'm curious how that wears over time.

column14: I was a little bit skeptical about purchasing this purse after reading some of the reviews. I am also extremely picky when it comes to purses. After thinking about it I decided to purchase this purse in purple. I found myself checking the USPS tracking almost daily because I was so excited. It did take about 3 weeks before I received this purse, but I also received it about a week earlier than the estimated arrival date. I did notice a small oder from the purse, probably from the processing and packaging but nothing that lasted for more than an hour or so. The inside of the purse has a nice circular pattern with a zipper pocket and two other smaller pockets. There is also a 3/4 zipper closure as well as a button, which I like for added security and peace of mind. Great size, exactly what I was looking for. I thought I would remove the longer strap but I like have the longer strap and the smaller handles. Color was exactly like it is in the pictures. I cannot comment on the longevity of this purse because I have not had it that long but so far I love it and it cannot wait to purchase this purse in both white and grey.

column6: Crocs Women's Shayna Mary Jane Shoe
column14:
WOW am I bummed! I purchased a pair of these shoes a good decade ago and have worn them to death. I loved that they were kind of just a more narrow version of the traditional clogs, which I also own and like but come on. They're so ugly.

Unfortunately I decided to wear them during our DIY home renovation (which was fabulously comfortable, by the way) and now they are covered in paint and plaster and what have you. Of course, in the back of my head, I thought "Hey this are totally replaceable. Just ruin them." Went and ordered a new pair on Amazon to discover they TOTALLY changed the design! UGH. The new ones now have a fixed back strap and are waaaaaaayyyy tighter that the original. Ordered the exact same size and they are too narrow, short and super tight. I hate them.

So upset. Returning.

I should mentioned I do loves me some crocs, though. These things are indestructible. Outside of the paint and plaster stains, the structure of mine look practically new!

column13: I wish I could wear slippers to work
column14:
I have recently been diagnosed with Plantar fasciitis and have been having an absolutely AWFUL time trying to find slippers and shoes of all kinds that don't hurt my feet.
I read the previous reviews on these slippers and ordered a size down from what I normally wear (I normally wear a size 9 and ordered an 8), they were exactly as I expected. I was also worried about these being slide on slippers because I have stairs in my house and I wanted to make sure that I wouldn't lose a slipper while going up and down. I have done that before so normally I wear closed back slippers.
I read in some previous reviews that these have a hook and loop closure to help with a secure fit, and that is accurate. I put them on the first time and closed them as tight as was comfortable and haven't had any incidents.
I really look forward to coming home at the end of the day and putting these on. I have told my husband multiple times "I wish I could wear slippers to work"
Thinking about buying other Orthaheel products.

Well I read some more reviews afterwards claiming that shoes from this seller are fake. I went to go take a closer look at mine and realized they are a 9.5W... Not only did I not order a wide, according to the Tom's website the company doesn't even sell shoes in wide, only medium. So glad I checked, as I was about to go ahead and just order the 9's. column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Kahana 6 Trail Running Shoe
column13: Great shoes; not the best Asics product
column14:
I love Asics. I decided my old ratty (but trusty!) ones were due for an upgrade so I bought these.

Unfortunately, these weren't quite what I expected from Asics. They were a little heavier, narrower and the material was a little stiffer. Perhaps it's all because they're meant for trail running. However, I found that while running on dirt, my lighter, slightly wider and more breathable old Asics performed the same. These weren't any less slick neither did they provide much more support related to cushioning and/or shock absorption. These perhaps keep the water from seeping into my shoes a little bit longer; however, not long enough to really matter to me.

They are still a great pair of shoes. They're lighter than most. They're durable and have great breathability. For some who moderately overpronates, these are great. Between the underfoot cushioning that provide extra support and the way it's built around your foot, I find that I feel safe that I won't roll my ankle in these.

As far as shoes go, these are still a great pair. As far as Asics shoes go, these are not my favorite.

column6: KEEN Women's Koven Hiking Shoe
column14:
I just got these the other day, so I will update this review if anything unexpected happens during the first few months of use, but I have multiple Keen sandals, all of which are the best shoes I've ever owned, and I expect these will follow suit!

These shoes have a great look, and I love the flashy spark of bright blue on the tongue and laces!! They fit like a dream. Although I can completely see how the mouth at the ankle might be a bit loose for some people, I have thick ankles and calves, and wide feet, and the 6.5M fit me very comfortably! And they are so light (especially for hiking shoes) that after a few minutes I forgot I was wearing them! I also have high arches, and these shoes have excellent support, and a thick sole with great grip and water resistance. I cannot wait to get out on the trail!! These are a fantastic deal, especially on sale for just under $50! My keen sandals have lasted me through daily wear and tear (I work outside most of the time), and are still going strong after 6+ years, and I hope for the same quality with these excellent hiking shoes. Highly recommended!

column6: AnyWear Women's Srangel Health Care & Food Service Shoe
column14: I'm an RN who's on my feet 13 hrs/day.  I had been wearing the Cherokee Pamela, but the top part of shoe was leaving an indentation on my foot because it was too tight, otherwise I loved that shoe.  I bought this shoe without having tried it on anywhere else, so it was a bit of a risk.  I wear a size 7.5 & bought an 8, but it was a little smaller than I expected.  It's super comfy, though, & after a couple weeks, it's stretched out some & I can wear my insoles.  My only "con" is that the actual support of the shoe (top & sides) is so soft that my feet felt more fatigued compared to the Pamela at the end of the day.  The heel, too, is a little lower than the Pamela's & I liked the height of the Pamela better.  But there's hardly any weight to the shoe, & it's very soft & comfy.  For my 13-hr workday, however, I might consider a shoe next time with a little stiffer support.

column6: Five Ten Women's Exum Guide Hiking Shoe
column13: Great for Caving--tested in Vietnam Jungle!
column14: I bought these for a four-night trek through the Vietnam jungle through the largest cave in the world, Son Doong. The caving experts recommended the Five Ten Canyoneer shoes but at nearly $200 I couldn't swing that. These have the same grippy sole that the Canyoneers have but they are much more affordable. I believe these were perfect for my needs. They were super grippy and we did a lot of rock climbing, both on wet and dry surfaces, and these soles made me like a gecko, especially compared to others in our group who had Keens and Merrells and the like. I also needed shoes that were not waterproof, as we would be crossing a lot of rivers and waterproof boots hold water. These did end up staying soggier than I would have liked, so that's my only beef with them. They were able to dry out in one day in an air conditioned hotel room upon our return, but our camps were too humid for them to dry completely during the trip. They were super comfortable for the duration of the journey. The terrain was extremely rough underfoot for most of the trip and these did a good job of keeping my feet stable. They do run small: I'm normally between an 8.5 and a 9 and I bought these in a 9.5 (the size I usually buy for running shoes) and they were perfect. So I would say get at least a half size up...if you're in between sizes, go a full size up from your smaller size. In the photo you can see they look a bit chunky but they served me well despite that. The photo is after two days of hiking through the jungle, crossing a river more than 30 times, and scrambling over lots of rocks. I definitely plan to use these again for camping and hiking stateside, as they are super comfortable. I would not have changed anything about my shoe selection for this cave trip, but if I were to do a longer amphibious trip where grippiness was less of a concern, I would go with something that dries more quickly. This was a solid purchase and I would definitely recommend this as a comfortable shoe that gripslike a gecko!

column6: Vionic with Orthaheel Amber Women's Sandal
column14: The concept for these sandals was good, but the execution left a lot to be desired, and I returned them. The foot bed felt great and the gold and cork color was reasonably attractive. The problem was the poorly designed straps. All of the cross straps and the ankle strap were too long. The cross straps had so much velcro on them that even when they were adjusted as tightly as possible, there was still exposed velcro which rubbed against the top of my foot. The ankle strap was so long that it looped around and overlapped the top cross strap, making for a very bulky, unattractive look. If someone had a foot so large that it required straps this long, their foot would not fit on the foot bed. Finally, on one sandal the ankle strap was stitched to the inside supporting strap at the wrong angle, causing it to bulge outwards. Poor manufacturing. If Vionic could pair its superior footbed design with high quality uppers made from good leather, they would probably sell a lot more sandals. Combine the Vionic footbed with a Joseph Seibel upper, and you'd really have something.

column6: PROYA Women's Double Zip Around PVC Leather Wristlet Clutch Organizer Wallet
column14:
I love this wallet so much. Although I was recently promoted to restaurant manager, I still have to waitress a few times a week. I need a wallet that can hold a couple hundred dollars worth of one dollar bills without breaking the zipper. This wallet does that and so much more.

I used to use a makeup bag to carry a wallet that held my wallet with cash, a change purse with all my coins, and a money clip to hold all my rewards cards. I've been able to condense this all into one single wallet. It has ample space to carry cash, tons of card slots to hold my numerous rewards cards for various places, and coins. I still have room for my receipts (I'm one of those few people who still use a check register to manage my checking account) without having to rip them out of the zipper because there's enough space.

I bought this wallet originally in taupe which was what I wanted at the time, but it's too boring for me (what did I expect!?). I sewed on a little patch to jazz it up a bit. That's not the wallets fault though, I should've known this when I ordered taupe haha. Should anything ever happen to this wallet, I'll just order another color. But I don't foresee anything happening to it anytime soon, it's built well and I just don't see it falling apart at all.

Wallets on the bigger side are so expensive in store. Seriously I bought a comparable wallet at target that was maybe a smidge smaller than this one years ago and it was in the 30 to 40 dollar range. That one had stylish buckles on it that frayed and fell apart after a month or two. So sometimes, it's nice to get a plain wallet. I mean come on, it's in your purse all the time, it's gonna get banged around and beaten up. With this wallet, you're not gonna have to worry about jewels or studs or buckles falling off and making your wallet look like junk. I highly recommend this.

I was not given this wallet for my review. I bought this with my own money and I'm giving you my honest opinion on it with no persuasion from any of the sellers.t opinion on it with no persuasion from any of the sellers.
