column6: Merrell Women's Swivel Leather Sandal
column14:
I was so looking forward to getting these sandals because my friend has a different model of Merrell sandals she bought in Europe and wears them all the time while walking all day, going everywhere and they are amazing. I wasn't able to find the model she has here in the US so I decided to give these ones a try.

I have to say I have pretty mixed feelings about these sandals and Merrel brand in general. First of all, based on all the reviews I've read and also my first experience with a different model I ordered from DSW (and returned), I went with a smaller size than mine. I'm a true 6.5 when it comes to most shoes, except for winter boots. Those I prefer in 7-7.5 so I can chose what thickness socks to wear. But for most sandals and flip flops and pretty much anything "open toe", anything in 6-6.5 works well. Typically. Well, not Merrell's apparently. The DSW pair I got in 7 was huge and left tons of space in front of my toes and didn't look as cute in reality so I returned it to the store. Found these ones and ordered them in size 6 to avoid the same situation I had with the other pair. Wrong again. The sole wasn't small. It was ok. No toes hanging over because my foot wouldn't even fit that far into the sandal lol

The very first strap (non adjustable and closest to your ankle that goes over the "instep") would not allow for my foot to go much further. Fine! I sent them back and exchanged for yet again, size 7. Size 7 of this style fits a bit better and the sole isn't too long like the other ones. Little room in front of my toes but nothing crazy. Straps are slightly wider but I'm still uncomfortable with the tightness of that instep strap :-( And the other strap you can adjust on these in the front doesn't really do anything. It's pretty much there for looks lol The front strap is surprisingly comfy for me but only because I have wide "duck" feet with all toes of the same length. so for anyone who has normal more pointy feet, it'll most likely be too wide :-(
I'm hoping that it'll stretch with time because it's leather and the sole is comfy. I can't say it gives amazing arch support. It seems to me that in order for that to happen, it would need to be more firm instead of soft but they do feel nice to walk in. I have yet to test them on a really long walk (5 miles +), but I'm keeping them simply because I need a pair of comfy walking sandals and I"m tired of exchanging them. Not sure I will buy Merrell's sandals again though. The whole "no half sizes" thing is pretty disappointing. All of the adjustment features they offer do not make up for weird sole sizes for all of us half size people and sometimes, the straps that need to be adjustable the most are not. Besides, they aren't exactly $39.99. I guess I expected more for the price :-( Time will tell if at least the quality makes up for fitment difficulties :-)

column6: Lamo Women's Merino Scuffs
column13: Real Shearling Wool, Exquisite Quality & Value !!!
column14:
Lamo (as in "Lamb") Women's Merino Scuffs vs. Ugg Coquette:

1st, RE: Size- These Lamo's run waaaay short. I wear a 9 in Ugg, size 10 in Frye boots & shoes, & size 9 or 10 XXW in Reeboks / Converse- In comparison, the XXL (11-12) Lamo is even smaller- (shorter length, same width- Hard to believe this, but true!) Since I'm sort of between a 9-10 in regular shoes (Wide Width), these XXL's are just barely long enough for my foot. (The cushy-ness will mat down over time, allowing my foot to slide deeper into the slipper). However: To be clear- They are nice & WIDE !!! otoh, the Shearling lining is sooo thick, it will likely custom-conform to any foot width- It's snugly / cushy on my wide foot. I know my wide Euro-feet will eventually squish down the Shearling to fit perfectly- And, I a normal width (or even a slightly narrow foot), would likely just squish the interior fluff to it's owner's foot contours. Really, it's sooo cushy! Feels heavenly :b

Not realizing how short these Lamo's run, I simultaneously ordered one size smaller for my daughter (sz. 8 Ugg Coquette, size 9 Women's shoe), which seem to be just 1/3" smaller, & roughly equivalent to size 8 Women's shoe (7 Women's Ugg!) Although the sizing is super-tiny, the sole is shaped in a fashion such that the big toe area is elongated, for a nice comforming fit to a real human foot.

2nd, RE: Lining- Make sure you get these MERINO Scuffs, otherwise the other models seem to be synthetic fluff-lined. But, these Merino Scuffs ARE true Shearling / Sheepkin lined (entire interior- Insole & Upper)- When you open the box, they smell like fresh, clean, new wool. They are off the chain cushy! Even better than Ugg! Seriously, they are sooo plush inside! I haven't worn them (other than try-on), so idk how they'll hold up, but they seem extremely solidly constructed!

3rd, RE: Sole- I haven't worn these yet, other than trying them on, but the sole seems perfectly sturdy, lightweight, & flexible, a bit thinner than my Ugg Coquettes perhaps.

4th, RE: Price/Value- When I 1st started buying Ugg Coquettes, they were ~ $100... I thought that price was absurd, but b/c I didn't think to comparison shop (until now), I wrongly assumed that Uggs were "the best", & I convinced myself that they were worth it... If I'm at home, my slippers are on, & I wear them out in the yard, driveway, to mailbox, even as quick teen - taxi Mom (driving)- I've been through 2 pair of Uggs, & the 2nd pair just didn't hold up well- The footbed lining was gone in a month (I had to buy replacement insoles, which work quite well, but cost yet another $20!). These Lamo's look, feel, and handle like an exquisitely constructed slipper, for 1/3 the price- Repeat- I can get THREE pairs of Lamo's, w/ much more plush lining, for the cost of ONE pair of competition.

5th, RE: Color- These Lamo's appear so much darker on-line, but, when placed side by side w/ my "Chestnut" Uggs (the standard neutral color, most-sold), these Lamo's appear (nearly) the same shade- OK, I guess 1 shade darker. I imagine that after wearing & laundering, they too might lighten up a bit in color. They are NOT nearly as dark as the picture appears, so please don't let the color dissuade you, unless you want a VERY pale shade. I cook in my slippers- They get olive oil, tomato sauce, & everything imaginable spilled on them- So, a mid-tan neutral color like this Lamo is perfecto!

I've included pix of my OLD size 9 Uggs, side by side w/ these NEW size XXL (11-12) Lamo's, for reference.

Final thoughts- My only regret is not discovering these earlier! Also look at "Old Friend" and "Bearpaw" slippers- But, read very carefully- Only select models are real Shearling-lined. They all seem to run ~ $40-$50. btw- Lamo offers Men's real Shearling slippers, too (but, reading reviews, they seem to run very small, too). Hope this helps, if you're on the fence!

column6: Suvelle Mens Genuine Leather Zippered Coin Pouch Change Purse Key Holder Money Organizer Wallet Stylish Gift For Men WP470
column14:
When I travel for pleasure, I like to travel light by transferring my essential credit cards and ID, along with cash to what I call a travel wallet. I bought this "coin purse" for that purpose. Overall it will work pretty good. Here are the pro's and con's as I see them:

PRO: Seems to be of sturdy construction. I like the fact that there are 2 compartments - so I put the credit cards and ID's on one side and the cash on the other. And the size - while at 5" it is just a wider than I need, overall it definitely works with some room to spare. Would not want it to be any bigger. NOTE: US credit cards are 3.375 inches wide and need at least a 4" opening to fit in. US currency folded in half is about 3" wide but slightly taller than 2.5". So the currency will only fit in a purse that is 2.5" tall if you fold it twice - which thickens it significantly. I like that with this purse I only need to fold the currency once.

CONS: I received it about a week ago and the strong leather aroma is just beginning to diminish. Hoping in another month when I take my next trip, the smell is gone. The leather while sturdy and well sewn, does not feel soft and supple. Rather it feels thin but sturdy. I don't think I got high quality leather, but then I did not pay for that either.

OVERALL: For what I want it to do - it will work fine ...... as long as the aroma eventually goes away. Recommended.

column6: Vionic Bryce Sandals with Orthaheel Technology
column13: Great Recovery Support For Runners Dealing With Plantar Pain
column14:
A few months back I started experiencing symptoms that seemed to be related to plantar fasciitis during my marathon training. I tried all sorts of suggested remedies, but I recently came to the conclusion that having arch support all day long would probably be my best bet for allowing my plantar to heal between workouts. I work from home and don't wear shoes the entire day. Walking around barefoot seemed to cause more aches and pains in my plantar by the end of the day. So after doing some research, I decided to splurge and get the Orthaheel Men's Bryce Thong Sandal after seeing great reviews on the product. I've been running seriously for the past 3+ years and one thing I've learned is to not go cheap on foot wear because that can make a big difference in being able to avoid injury. So I looked at the Orthaheel sandal as an investment in my well-being as a runner.

The first time I tried them on, I was immediately impressed. The arch support instantly made my feet feel better. My plantar could relax while I was walking around and it was such a relief! I have neutral arches and these sandals felt comfortable from the get-go. No break in period needed. I wear them all day long now- even when I use the bathroom in the middle of the night, I slip these sandals on to avoid going barefoot at all. It's been two weeks and I finally feel like I've got a handle on my plantar fasciitis issues. I highly recommend these sandals!

column13: Beautiful purse and the handles have a touch of pink, which I love!
column14:
[[VIDEOID:6cc453121436a27bd4eaf03b89060e89]]I have to be honest, I got this purse in spite of the alligator pattern as that is normally not my style, but I think it's ended up being one of my favorite aspects of the purse! The handles are a mixture of pink, white, and blue in an alligator print and I have to admit I'm a huge fan on pink so this has become my favorite new purse.

I'm not a fan of small purses so I love the roominess of this purse. It has two large pockets inside it, with a zippered pouch separating them which I love. Let's face it, there are just some things you don't want hanging out of your purse, and this middle zippered pouch will keep your private items private! If you aren't a big fan of handles it does come with a removable strap, so it's very versatile.

I'm a big fan of the little small touches, and when you order this purse it actually comes in a dust bag, which is a nice touch to me. It also comes with a scented satchel and these cute little clips. Little touches like this definitely make a brand stand out for me, and turn me into a repeat customer. The quality is phenomenal to me. I received the dark blue bag and it's a little lighter than pictured, but I learned a long time ago there are often shade variances when purchasing items like this online and I'm extremely pleased with this purse!

I received this product at a discounted rate in exchange for my honest, unbiased opinion.

column6: Hee Grand Mens Canvas Slip on Shoes Sneakers
column14:
tl;dr: Great looking, inexpensive shoe that fits as expected but is not durable and has zero support.

Pros:
- The shoes look amazing. My first thought upon opening the package was "wow, those are kick-ass."
- Amazon's picture doesn't do the shoe justice. The green material has a great texture. I was blown away by the interior pattern (something Scottish, right?)
- Fit. I ordered a size 10 and they fit very well (without socks). For context, I wear the following sizes with socks (unless otherwise noted): 10 (Converse; Influence w/o socks;Timberland; Hugo Boss dress shoes w/ dress socks) and 11 (Allen Edmond w/ dress socks; Tiger; Asics)
- Did I mention they look amazing?

Cons:
- Doesn't look sturdy (why 4 and not 5 stars)
- I don't wear socks w/ slip-ons, but if you do, order up a size
- Not Prime Eligible and took ~20 days to get to Brooklyn from China. I forgot I ordered them!

I will update the review after I've taken them for more of a spin.

column13: DO YOU WANT A GREAT PAIR OF SHADES AT A REASONABLE PRICE???  MAMBO SHADES ARE WHAT YOU ARE LOOKING FOR!!
column14:
These are a nice set of polarized sunglasses!!
Key features:

** Polarized lenses
** Durable resin frames
** 58mm L x 45 mm W
** Bridge: 21 mm, Arm: 137 mm
** Carry pouch

I only wear polarized lenses. I had laser eye surgery several years ago and polarized lenses are designed to eliminate reflective glare and to protect against harmful UVA and UVB rays. Many regular lenses do not do that.

I used to only wear a particular name brand polarized lense that I would pay between $150 to $250 for. I no longer have to shell out a ton of money to get quality sunglasses to protect my now perfect vision eyes.

Mambo shades are a quality product that you can trust. The price is in line with the quality of the product. I have had the pleasure to test several types of polarized lenses in their wonderful line of sunglasses. I have been completely satisfied with each one. My pre-teen boys have a favorite pair of their mambo shades too!!

* I received this product at a discount in exchange for an honest and unbiased review.

column6: Townforst Women's Slip Resistant Sophia Shoes No Slip Shoes
column13: These shoes look much better in person than the picture
column14: I bought these shoes because I teach and spend a lot of time on my feet, and I have had plantar fasciitis in the past which I do not want to aggravate.  I'm starting a new job in the fall where I need shoes that are more professional looking than the running shoes I had been wearing when I teach.  These shoes look much better in person than the picture, and I'm very glad I bought them.  They will serve the purpose of completing my professional wardrobe while being comfortable at the same time.  The insoles are so cushiony, as soon as I slipped them on, I knew I'd made the right decision.  I have an issue with my right foot being a bit wider in the toe area than my left.  If I buy shoes 1/2 size bigger, they are too big, so I bought my normal size.  The shoes fit fine, but I'm still using my stretcher to get just a tinch more toe space in the right shoe.  That is not the manufacturer's fault; that's my foot problem, so I still gave the shoe 5 stars.  I love that they are leather, a good height (can't wear heels for long and flats are uncomfortable). I have a lot of issues with my feet, and I'm picky about the look of the shoes I wear, so I feel I hit the mother lode with these particular shoes.  I'm ready to buy a couple more pair so I have them when these wear out. (I will be wearing them a lot!)

column6: Toms Women's Classic Crochet Natutal/Morocco Casual Shoe 5 Women US
column14:
These are AWESOME shoes. I own a lot of TOMS (24+ pairs and counting), but these are one of my go-to shoes for every day wear. They are perfect for the beach and summer weather, and the natural color matches with just about anything.

As with buying other TOMS, you would need to size down a half to full size because they stretch over time. One thing to consider, however, is that that TOMS shoes are notoriously inconsistent in sizing. That means that you can buy 2 pairs of the exact same shoes, and one pair can be CONSIDERABLY larger than the other, even though in theory, they should both be the exact same size. In fact, I have even received TOMS where one shoe is noticeably larger than the other inside the same shoe box. This means that if you KNOW you are a size 5 in Toms, and the shoes you received are too big or too small, you may want to try another size 5 again because the pair you received may have just been "off." Luckily, Amazon has an awesome return policy, so exchanging is never a problem.

I will be going to Europe soon, and these crochet TOMs along with the glitter silver ones are coming along with me!

column6: Scarleton Zipper Washed Shoulder Bag H1472
column13: Great bag! I love the color
column14: Great bag! I love the color, size and the shoulder or crossbody strap option.  I have had trouble finding bags with the shoulder and crossbody straps in the past, so I really appreciate this feature.  I have also had trouble finding this dark brown "coffee" color in the past year, so I was thrilled to discover the Scarleton brand last month which seems to offer lots of its bags in this color.  This is a large bag, but it doesn't appear like an overnight bag, gym bag or carry-on.  I find the size perfect for my needs.  I can pack everything I normally bring with some room to spare... for example: large wallet, 5"x7" 100-page tablet and pen, glasses, standard plastic pencil box, 16 ounce water bottle and baseball cap.  The bag has a good number of compartments for organizing, and each compartment is a reasonable size.  This is a floppy bag, made with a very soft synthetic leather which I like, but if you are looking for structure it does not have it. The only thing I would actually change about this bag is the black paint on the buckles.  I wish it was the same silver color as the rest of the buckle.  However, the color scheme of the buckles matches the brand label in the center so it still looks good. It was also a very good price.  I am thrilled to have found this bag and this brand!

column13: Go a size up at the very least but some design flaws

column6: Merrell Women's Pace Glove 3 Trail Running Shoe
column14:
The Pace Glove 3 is the most perfect shoe ever devised. I absolutely loved the Pace Glove 2 and the PG 3 is slightly better in some ways. Somewhere between the PG 2 and 3 is the best shoe you can ever imagine. I like the aesthetics of the PG 3, but it's possible the PG 2 version was very slightly better.

What makes this shoe so special, is not merely the low weight - these shores weigh almost nothing - but they way they allow my hooves to communicate with the ground. In terms of being able to move biomechanically efficiently, there is nothing like them that I know of that are this good. I have a particular need for a specific shoe for tai chi.

This shoe, both versions, handle both slow tai chi, and fast tai chi unbelievably well. If I compare them to shoes that do not have this design, then, these shoes actually advantage my tai chi slightly, versus shoes that do not or make it harder to feel the ground forces and internal kinetics of movement as you move. But as with anything, if you are not ready for a shoe of this type, then it's only going to augment your tai chi so far.

This is more for Merrell's Design Staff than customers, but you have a unique shoe here of great value to someone with the right set of needs or wants. I can't imagine bothering to wear anything else unless I absolutely had to. I already own three pair of the black PG 3 and had two pair of the black and pink PG 2 until I lost one pair. Please consider making at least one model of the Pace Glove in black every year or season. Maybe you guys would be willing to do a limited production run or something, to make ten or so pairs of Pace Glove 3 with the Vibram sole from the PG 2, and the interior color, and external pink striping and laces which looks very nice. and then use the same mesh and taping techniques from the PG 3, on the hybrid model. That would be the best shoe that ever graced my hooves. Until next time.

column6: Caterpillar Men's Brode Hi Steel Toe Skate Shoe
column14: This shoe is too narrow at the toes.  I wear a size 9.5 in Nike's (universal standard).  I started wearing Cats work boots because my first pair of Second Shift boots lasted me a couple years through some tough use and abuse and I wore a 8.5 in those.  Then I found the Caterpillar Men's Streamline Comp Toe Running Shoe,Medium Charcoal, and I figured on getting a size 9 regular width.  It fit too narrow around the toes and after a couple hours felt really uncomfortable.  Of course by then I had worn them to the point of no return.  That was a year ago and I"ve had to deal with the discomfort long enough and it's time for  a new pair so I found these Caterpillar Men's Brode Hi ST Work Boot,Black,and decided to get 9.5 regular width.  Still too narrow.  It's not the size, it's the width.  Now I am convinced that I should have gotten a 9.5 wide.  Anyway, I had bought these shoes on a Amazon lightning deal, and now that I have to return it, I don't know if there is a way to get the same price from the lightning deal in a different size.  I hope Amazon sees this comment and sends me a response.  Update 8/11/15:  I returned the regular width and got the wide width version.  Amazon did honor the lightning deal price, so kudos to them for providing excellent customer service.  Now on to the shoe.  Even the wide width version is too narrow at the toes.  It did seem wider at the midsole, but that's not where I need it wider.  It felt like Cat used the same steel toe as the regular width version, so it pretty much defeated the purpose of getting the wider width!  I really like the style of the shoe.  the black leather and red stitching is really bad a55, but too bad they couldn't get the sizing right.  I'm going to try the Reebok Leelap's as I have read reviews that those offer generous toe box.

column13: I also really like the fact that these don't have a frame bar ...
column14: I am really liking these glasses.  I needed a pair for cycling, for both road and mountain, which were light, stayed in place, and had clear optics.  I looked at some more expensive brands in the $200-300 range, and just could not bring myself to spend that when the probability of a crash on the mountain bike is always in the back of my mind when doing the real technical stuff (This is how I have scratched the lens on two pairs already over the past couple of years).  I also really like the fact that these don't have a frame bar across the top of the glasses allowing for a better view of the road while I am down on the drops on my road bike, and they are really light weight. The optic is very clear, and provides excellent glare protection during mid day rides.  These glasses are exceptional for the price.  I will be buying another pair just to have as a back up!!

column6: Ivanka Trump Women's Carra Dress Pump
column13: I noticed that the left shoe seemed it fit funny after the first or second wear
column14: Although I purchased these shoes over the summer, I've only worn them maybe three or four times - they're suede, and therefore a more winter shoe.  I noticed that the left shoe seemed it fit funny after the first or second wear, and as I'm wearing them today, I realize that it's because the sole of the shoe (right above the ball of the foot) is broken on the inside. I've had shoe heels break before, but I've never had the center of the shoe break in a way which makes it very difficult and uncomfortable to try and wear the show - whenever my left foot makes contact with the ground, the shoe's natural response is to buckle under, since the stability has been thrown off by the break. If I had had a wonderful experience with my other Ivanka Trump shoes, I would write this off as a fluke, but I feel like the quality has gone downhill, which the price has stayed the same.  I will not be purchasing these shoes again, and unfortunately, there didn't seem to be an outlet to reach out to 6PM to discuss replacement options.

column13: and is a nice blend of rugged and stylish
column14:
Full disclosure: I haven't had these boots long, and so I may update this review in the future to reflect changes in my opinion.

The shoes seem to be well made, and is a nice blend of rugged and stylish. They run just a half size large in my experience. The material is sturdy, and will require some working in to maximize comfort. For instance, due to the lack of a natural crease along to top portion of the boot, the material rebounds with each step. This was at first quite annoying, but became both less noticeable and less significant as I wore them more and more. Be forewarned that the soles are made of rubber, and they will squeak mercilessly on tile flooring. Overall, I am quite satisfied with this boot. It filled my needs well, and is being sold for an excellent price that seems to closely parallel its quality.

column6: Timberland PRO Men's Rigmaster Steel-Toe 8\ Waterproof Work Boot"
column13: the boots are of good quality and if not for the reason expressed
column14: The boots are marked wide but they fit as narrow size boots; they crimped my toes together tightly (these are steel tipped boots) that my small toes hurt.  I called Timberland to return the boots and explained the reason and she informed me that this style maybe the exception as being sized as wide but fit as narrow.  If that is the case their product across the line are not standardized, i.e. size wide is should be wide and not narrow, and size narrow should be narrow.  If not, it's a hit or miss to buy their product.  Other than this, the boots are of good quality and if not for the reason expressed, the boots have a natural step to them even out of the box and I feel would have no break-in period. She gave me an return material authorization (RMA), but a day afterwards I cancelled the RMA because I managed to cushion my small toes so that they do not crimp badly and are acceptable to walk my dog. I chose these boots because they are rated water proof, but as of yet it has not rained in central Texas in over 35 days.  If they fix their sizing at the toes, these boots would definitely be five stars. One more thing, do not return these boots by way of Amazon because OutdoorEquipped is the shipper and their return policy applies. If the fault is not their doing they may charge up to 20% stocking fee and charge you for the original shipping cost that will be applied against your refund.  Instead call Timberland because they have a "during first 30 days of no questions ask" policy return on their Powerfit series footwear, but do it within two (2) days of the end of the 30-day test period. But the refund does not include applicable taxes and/or shipping charges for return and they require receipts.

column6: Salomon Men's Speedcross 3 CS Trail Running
column14:
I previously had the regular Speedcross 3s so I knew what to expect size-wise and with respect to feel. They fit like most other running shoes on the market, as far as I can tell, but have a much better arch support. Oddly, I have tried a few other Salomon hiking shoes and boots with the OrthoLite sole but they never quite felt right, this shoe, however, is heavenly for my feet. So, I would suggest trying them on before you buy them if at all possible, even if you have other Salomon OrthoLite products.

I opted for the CS version this time because I have had a few instances of wet feet while camping with the regular version so it made sense when I finally wore out the regular pair I had. As other commenters have noted, these will not last long on paved streets, they belong on an unpaved trail. On pavement or hard flooring the treads will wear down significantly in a matter of weeks (~<2 weeks). Since I wear mine mostly on trails I got a good 8 months of heavy use out of the regular 3s. Also, until the tread does wear down it is so aggressive under the forefoot that it will hurt to walk on hard surfaces for extended periods.

column6: Merrell Men's Mojave Hiking Shoe
column13: A New Headliner for Merrell Shoes
column14: After weeks in Europe on cobblestone roads and walks my regular cross training shoes were a complete wreck. Merrill is a great known brand for hiking and good walking. I looked at several styles and while the ventilator models were good they seemed to let in too much moisture, this one had a nice look, good protection anti-roll for the ankles, and good padding for a walking shoe. They are $10 cheaper just due to the fact they do not have the name brand "Vibram" outer grip on the bottom but the present outer sole is great. My foot is narrow but is larger at the toes which tends to give me blisters, but Merrell adds a touch a extra width in the ball and toe area and these fit like a glove, are lightweight, and comfortable for a full day of walking.  They are not waterproof and in winter you may wish to switch to about or a waterproof version, but for long walks in Asia, Europe and beyond these are terrific. It is answer model for Merrell and we will see how long the interior sole lasts, but Merrell makes it easy to slip in a new sole.

column14: These were my first pair of Docs. I'm usually a U.S. women's size 6-6.5. Size 3 was too snug (my toes were a little uncomfortable because they were kind of squished) and the 4 is way too big. I agree with other reviewers that this is a very clunky shoe. Maybe it looks that way because I have a slim frame, but compared it with other Docs and the Flora boot is visibly chunkier. When not on the foot, the shoes look super sleek. Since the shaft is sort of high, it will hurt your heel unless you wear tall socks, especially when going down stairs. The boot itself is also really stiff, although that might just be the way it's supposed to be. After wearing them consistently for almost two weeks, my toes, the bridge of my foot, and my heel still hurt. I hope these eventually stop hurting my feet, because I do like them, even if they do make my feet look huge.

column13: Conformable, versatile. Fit true to size (for a wide-feet individual).
column14: These ankle boots are conformable, versatile with a kick of autumn flare, and they fit true to size (for a wide-feet individual). As you see in these photos, there is room around the ankle, which is a plus and preferable to me because it helps me flex my ankle when I walk, and for that I'm happy! For I have wide feet, I usually struggle to fit in boots size 7.5M-9M, especially boots with almond-toe design. So I was literally happy when my feet could fit comfortably in these shoes in size 8M (width: 3-5/8- 3.75 inches; length: 10 inches). The footbed is wide, the vamp is roomy. I think I'd be able to go 1/2 a size down without trouble. Therefore, if you have wide feet like I do, I'd suggest to with your true boots size or the smallest size of your boots-size range. If you have narrower feet or slender feet, I'd recommend to go at least 1 size down. These boots are a steal!

column6: Saucony Men's Virrata 2 Running Shoe
column14: This is an extremely light running shoe, weighing in at 7.4 oz (size 11). There is plenty of padding around the collar and tongue as well as good arch support and additional padding supplied by the removable footbed. Please note that the Virrata 2 has no heel to toe offset, in case that would be a problem for you. The shoe is very flexible, and the sole, with a tread pattern quite different from Saucony's Mirage 4, appears to be very cushiony. It does, however, have a high-abrasion material at the heel and the toe.  The upper is breathable mesh, and the lacing system is standard...with good ol' flat laces.

column6: Clarks Women's Delsie Bliss Dress Pump
column14: My favorite pair of pumps! I should note that my feet are slightly wide, so this might not be the best choice for someone with a really narrow foot, because this fits me perfectly width-wise. Normal width and slightly wide-footed gals should scoop these up. I have these in the nude patent and the black suede...for some reason, the black suede feels way more comfortable than the nude patent, but they're both great, and for someone with problem feet like me, the fact that I can run around in them all day at work and only have my feet swell up minimally at night when I go home (which happens with everything except sneakers), it's pretty awesome. I've also worn the black ones out to dinner with a moderate amount of walking to/from the restaurant and the train, and my feet were fine (which is amazing b/c I never walk around in heels -- I wear flats and change into heels for work or events). I wish they had the teal suede in my size! The only slight issue is that my foot does sometimes slip out of the back (only on one foot, the one that's slightly smaller), but I think I can fix this easily with a heel grabber from my shoe repair place.

column6: Sperry Top-Sider Men's A/O Boat Shoe
column13: QUALITY, or lack thereof, VARIES WIDELY
column14: I hope this is a good pair - they're made in Indonesia, not China.  The soles seem to be made of a new material, and the leather uppers have a different appearance than what I'm used to.  I have owned at least six pair of Sperry "Original" Topsiders over the decades.  The original US-Made quality was great - the soles of a 30+ year old pair are still intact.  My several Chinese "originals"  have varied tremendously in quality.  The soles of my most recent Chinese pair are crumbling into tiny pellets of hard plastic that scatter all over the floor - I've worn them as indoor slippers exclusively for two years as they are too fragile to wear outdoors.  I keep two other pair as beach shoes, and they have not disintegrated as badly despite sand, salt, and age.  I spoke to a company rep a few years ago to complain about the stitching coming apart, and he was the one who told me they'd been making shoes in China for at least 10 years.  "Originally" Sperry was an American company.  They've disintegrated from being a quality shoemaker crafting one good shoe into an international joke manufacturing dozens (hundreds?) of low quality "styles".  ORIGINAL?  My foot!

column13: B-width fit and Asics comfort - but wish for a better color and trail version in this width
column14: I love the comfort and smooth ride of the Gt 2000 3, but the D width fits a bit sloppy for running on uneven surfaces, i.e., trails and hills. The B width fits only slightly more snug, but it makes a difference, especially in the heel. Significant yet unobtrusive stability is built into these shoes, but Asics has reduced the amount arch support with each successive integration of the Gt-2000 line. So, for an even better fit, I swap out the insoles with Spenco Total Support.  For long training runs, the combination is about as close to perfect as I've found.  While the foot-to-ground transistion comfort is as good as it gets on uneven terrain, one downside is that it takes some fussing with the lacing to get the instep tolerable without being too loose. Also, the shiny-white plastic-looking color scheme is a bummer.  I wish Asics would make the B width in a more neutral and/or stylish gray or black like the trail version, but they don't.  (I'm 6' 3", 210 lbs., size 13B)

column6: Vivobarefoot Men's Stealth On Road Run Walk Shoe
column13: kids can be disgusting and who knows what stuff they track into a ...
column14: Living on the coast of California, I hardly wear shoes.  I have become accustom to walking barefoot and the unique challenges that one might face when doing away with traditional shoes (actually wearing typical athletic shoes hurts, a lot!).  I purchased these shoes to wear while I coach gymnastics, because let's face it... kids can be disgusting and who knows what stuff they track into a large gym.  The shoes are great, I can still maintain a near barefoot tactile feel with my feet, something that is important in gymnastics.  The shoes also add minimal weight to my feet so, when I demonstrate advanced flipping and twisting skills there isn't a requirement to adjust for the added weight and limitations a traditional athletic shoe offers.  I have even had other coaches in the gym inquire about these shoes, and as a result they have grown in popularity throughout the staff.  Sure there are other "bare foot" shoes out there for a better price point, but these have been some of the best shoes I have found as of late.

column6: OAKLEY Fuel Cell Polarized Sunglasses
column14:
Fantastic sunglasses. I have had these now for over 2 years, and I can't suggest these glasses enough. I've had various sunglasses over the course of 5 - 6 years, and I can say with a good degree of certainty that these glasses are the best investment I ever made.

They fit very well, and even cover the sides of my eye so that there is no sunlight directly hitting my eye in any way. I have worn these for 8 - 12 hours without taking them off, and they do a great job with protecting my eyes.

After some elongated use I did notice that the piece that sits on the ear does start to apply pressure to where it's sitting on the ear (after about an hour or so), and it can be slightly painful, but a quick adjustment of the glasses alleviates this. I wish there was some sort of padding or something that would help reduce this, but overall it's a minor issue.

Through the years the lenses have gotten mildly scratched up, because of my own usage and storage ineptitude (I had no idea you shouldn't put them in your pocket), but had I purchased a hard case for them, they probably would still look brand new. Although I try extremely hard to care for these glasses, and generally take great care of them, these have been dropped a couple of times. However, there is absolutely no evidence of their collision with the ground.

These glasses are durable and absolutely worth the money and will last a very long time.

Note - I purchased the polarized version of these glasses, as I wanted the glare protection and UV protection associated with the lenses. I have not worn the non-polarized versions, except in the store, but I would highly suggest to get polarized. It's worth the upgrade in money, and you'll notice a huge difference.

column14: I'm on my third pair of Romys, and I love them.  They cushion your foot and give excellent support for both the arches and the ankles. I walk/hike 7 days a week, getting in 3-5 miles per day on weekends when the hubby comes with me, and 5-8miles per day on weekdays. And when I remove my shoes when I get home, it's not because my feet hurt, but because I want to allow them to dry or because they need to be cleaned. These are one of the best walking shoes I've found...comfortable straight out of the box with no break in period needed, no rubbing, no sore spots. And what I like the most about them is that they're leather...so there are no rips or tears like I get with fabric shoes. One good sticker-bearing vine that gives a tug on my foot could result in a tear on shoes with fabric or mesh on the uppers...but with leather, those same vines just slide off of them. Which equates to a much longer shoe life. I'm averaging about 800 miles on a pair, and by then I replace them not because they're worn out, but because, being leather they don't breath well, and become rather smelly.  Lol However, I just purchased a shoe dryer that I'm hoping will alleviate that problem, too.

column6: New Balance Men's MX857 Cross-Training Shoe
column13: I've had some great new balance products
column14:
I bought mine at the new balance store locally. I've had some great new balance products, until this shoe. They didn't have my size in stock, so I let them have it shipped to my house. It came with a hole under the insole and not all the eyelets cut out. I returned them, they sent me another. They arrived fine, but 3 months later the leather on the side was tearing at the stitching. They replaced them. Again 3 months later the leather was tearing at the side. They decided they had me in the wrong size,replaced with different size, no problems for 6 more months. I was very understanding and really appreciative of all the replacements, heck I've bought at least 6 other pairs there prior, no issues. After 6 months the glue that holds the shoe to the upper quit. On the side of the left shoe, the toe of the right, big holes.

Anyway, that was the only time I tried the 857. I had really wanted a black leather laceup and that was the best option at the time. Now that I needed to replace the 857, they have another choice. I got the 1540, so far the quality seems much better. This is the only chance they get. I should have pushed them to replace the 857 again, they look brand new still, except where the glue let go.

column6: Dansko Men's Professional Clog
column14:
Pharmacist, standing 10-12 hrs a day, very little walking. Online research for best support all suggested Dansko clogs. Somewhat skeptical of the clog idea. Clogs? Daughter's an RN at a large hospital, worn Dansko's forever, swears by them. Asked her if any MEN wear them. She laughed. Yes, many do. Nothing particularly feminine about a black / brown clog. No one notices or cares. They allow you to be on your feet all day on hard surfaces. Great advice.

Plusses: By far the best support I've ever had. Feet no longer hurt at the end of the shift. Initially tight across the top, loosened up quickly. Have worn many big-name support shoes over the years, these top them all.

Caveat: 2" heels had a learning curve. Walking's not bad, but lateral movements were a challenge. Moving side to side (between bays) took some practice. Now easy.

Non-verified purchase, came from E/Bay.
Next pair (very soon!) will come from Amazon, they're available in extra width, a plus. Need just a bit more wiggle room in the toes.

column13: HELP I HAVE PLANTAR FASCITIS AND I DON'T HAVE TOO-------------------------
column14: I have a COMMENT about Plantar Fasciitis.  Please don't suffer from this debilitating condition.  I'm a retired EMT who had this problem more than 20 years ago.  There's such a simple fix.  Go to an orthopedic surgeon for an outpatient procedure.  He/She will make a small incision probably less than 1" and cut the nerve that is giving you all the pain over the spur that is the problem.  I had mine done more than 20 years ago. I can't remember which foot it was or see the incision.  The recovery time was very short. I haven't had any problems with it since.  All the exercise and inserts may work but they're expensive and time consuming only to have it come back.  You may find a podiatrist willing to do this procedure as well. You don't have to suffer any more.  In the future make sure you wear good fitting shoes.

column6: This War of Mine (PC DVD) (UK IMPORT)
column14:
This is listed as a PC DVD. I expected that the software would be on the DVD. This is a lie.
It does not have the actual game on the DVD.
However it requires a third party software called "Steam" to be installed before you can play the game.
Furthermore "Steam" requires internet access.
Furthermore "Steam" requires you to create an account with them.
Furthermore "Steam" requires you to enter their activation code on the paperwork in the DVD case.
Then "Steam" pulls down the game from the internet - 1.4 GB across whatever bandwidth you have.
"Steam" takes whatever information it can from your pc.
"Steam" tracks any activity and achivements that you do in the game.
"Steam" tracks how many hours you played the game, when purchased, when last used.

You cannot play this without Steam. There is no desktop shortcut, no task bar shortcut, and no
"Start Program" shortcut to the game. You have to start and connect to Steam to play the game.

Steam installs DirectX for Windows, MS Visual C++ Redistributable, etc. on your pc.

I have two monitors. The game only plays on one of them.

After you exit the game, you get to see ads shown by "Steam" by third party vendors in the form of "Update News".

Uninstall "Steam" and you cannot play the game.

column6: Anno: 1404 - Gold Edition
column13: DVD is missing CAB file - also has DRM
column14:
As several other reviewers have mentioned, the installer package on the DVD is assembled incorrectly - a CAB file is missing - and therefore the installation aborts. The game will not install, let alone run. And there is nothing to patch because nothing was installed. This may be for the English language installation only, and may pertain only to the current (August, 2015) batch of DVDs being shipped.

Straight into the trash.

Even if you get a good DVD with complete installation on the DVD, note that Anno 1404 will install the Tages DRM system onto your computer! Tages is an invasive DRM system that has received hundreds of thousands of user complaints. Therefore, the v1.1 patch of the game removes the reliance on Tages (which never worked correctly), but leaves Tages installed on your computer, doing bad things.

Basically, you should avoid Anno 1404 at all costs, even if you have a pure game machine you don't mind getting trashed.

My recommendation is to go backwards to the original game, Anno 1602 ("1602 AD" in the U.S.).

column6: Fire Emblem: Awakening
column13: This was a great game. Just to give you guys a background
column14:
This was a great game. Just to give you guys a background, I have played the first fire emblem(logged over 200 hours), Sacred stones, Shadow dragon, and now this one. I love love love fire emblem ever since the first game, moreover, I love the idea of nomads coming together to fight a bigger cause.

There were many mechanics that differ from the old ones like marriages, skills, dual battles, defensive maps and no arenas. With these new mechanics, this game is still splendid. The graphics and the art were gorgeous. The gameplay is like the other fire emblem but there is no "rescue". You can pair with other players to battle together. Skills is probably the best and the worst part of this game. It takes FOREVER to grind the skills you want, but on the bright side, your character becomes unstoppable (Galeforce, Limit breaker, vantage/venegance.) I love the fact that there is no arena because frankly, the arena idea just sucks. My only major complaint is that there were NO defensive maps in this game. Maybe only one defensive map. In all the of the previous fire emblems, defensive maps were just as difficult as the offensive ones. It changes the tactics and how to use your troops.

All in all, it was a great game and it's worth the purchase.

column6: Dying Light
column13: Too Much of Been There, Done That
column14:
While obviously trying to be so many games wrapped up in one, Dying Light fails to capture this gamer's interest by being incredibly inaccessible with a complicated mix of previous games. It truly sputters any spark of immediate feel-good action or originality. What do I mean? Let's take a simple idea about going from point A to point B, kind of like Grand Theft Auto where you have to traverse halfway around the map and back just to accomplish nothing important. And while you're going from point A to B, you also need to go to point C, D and E because there are side missions that are somehow important too. Now let's add parkour, cause hey, it's cool and hip. Mirror's Edge it is. But it's not a simple button press to accomplish this parkour. You must be specifically looking at what you need to jump to in order to actually make any successful jump. Now we need bad guys in the story cause if everyone was good, the game would REALLY suck. Far Cry it is, because it resembles an open world while actually being very linear. Ok. But we need a hook. Something to make it seem not so copycatish to all the other games. I got it! ZOMBIES! Dead Island it is! Because hitting zombies over the head with a super-duper modulated rusty pipe is much more enjoyable than laying waste to hundreds of them with a full-auto 50 cal. or BFG. So we have a Dead Island, Mirror's Edge, Far Cry, GTA remix. Great, right?? Not if you played those games before. Mixing it all together turns it into a much too complex layering of things to do and stuff to manage while simply going from point A to point B becomes a migraine within a headache within a hemorrhoid ready to burst.

If you don't feel frustrated playing this game, you are special. And by being special, you will always get to ride on the short bus--from point A to point B, to C, D and F.

column6: Destiny
column13: Solid core with insulting progression and (lack of) substance
column14: I have the digital version purchased through Xbox Live and have had the game for about 10 months.  I did not buy any of the expansions and don't intend to do so in the future.  When a company offers an online-required product, it should put forth its best effort to ensure it provides stable access to the server for the clients. With Destiny, Bungie has not, and even after nearly a year, there is still a menagerie (errors are named after animals in Destiny) of error codes and disconnects from Live that I and many others face. It makes it hard to review a product that stops you from using it every few minutes. Not everyone has this issue (there seems to be an ISP routing issue depending on your geographical location), but its still widespread, and nothing appears to be happening to fix it. This is not a problem I experience on ANY other game. See the Bungie forums on errors and networking.  This is too bad, because the core gunplay of the single and cooperative modes of the game are really quite good. Enemy and weapon/skill variety is satisfying and finding or earning upgrades to your gear and character is nice.  ...For a time.  The base game content can be cleared in a handful of hours. There are very few locations and after reaching level 20 you must complete daily and weekly challenges (the same missions you've already done, but with enemies that hit harder and go down more slowly) or play PVP, which has a few modes, but is uninteresting and isn't a great way to progress because the other players will have superior gear. Rewards are not based on performance, however, so you may have someone on your team who stays at the spawn point during the entire run receive the best reward after the mission while those who carry the team get nothing. Same is true of PVP. Eventually you'll have to buy the DLC to progress, which grants some additional new content, but is quite pricy, and with a new Taken King version of the game incoming, buying the base game, if you're interested in it, is a bad investment, considering the amount of content you'll be locked out of and the likelihood of your equipment being outdated when the expansion hits.  Music is nice. Graphics are good. Even though there seems to be some intricate lore behind the game, it's BEHIND the game; the acting and story are minimal and generally bad to mediocre.  Because this game has significant connection issues, fails to reward players for performance, gates progression with expensive DLC, and becomes a repetitive grind after a few hours, I can't recommend it, despite the fun and polished gameplay.

column6: Grand Theft Auto III
column14: When I downloaded this game to my computer the first time, the game worked like normal. It was fun, had better graphics than the PS2 version, and was an enjoyable 20 minutes. Remember what I said. One thing I really liked was the ability to use free aim on any of the guns, which made gunfights easier. After I was done playing for a while, I quit the game and did other things I normally do on my computer. I then decided to play this again. Only this time, the game won't load. When I click the icon, the hourglass, which would normally signify a program is loading on Windows, pops up for only 2 seconds and them disappears. I tried spamming the icon and the game still won't load. I tried it all; logging off and back on, shutting down, restarting and the game still would not work. This made me very angry. GTA 3 on PC, a game I had been hyping for months, and it doesn't work. Rockstar, you wouldn't have these issues if GTA 3 for PC was just a straight port of the PS2 version with improved graphics and controls. The error said something about gta3.exe, but that wasn't a problem at all. I do not know what is wrong with this game on PC. Hopefully Vice City's PC port (even though the PS2 version hasn't been released yet) will fix these issues. Shameless, Rockstar :(

column6: Pokemon Gold
column13: One of the best games in the series!! NOTE: game save issue is FIXABLE!!!!
column14:
This is one of the best games in the entire Pokemon series, if not one of the best handheld games ever made!! I bought this used back in around 2004, and last year I noticed that my game reset every time I started it up. It briefly upset me, but some quick internet research led me to see that the internal battery is a simple coin battery that can be replaced at home! I bought a replacement battery at target and found a specialty screwdriver online to open up the cartridge. In 10 minutes I had the game up and running like new. So, please don't toss the game in the trash if it isn't holding a save!!

As for the game play, you essentially get two games in one. After exploring and earning the 8 Johto badges, you get to go do the same in Kanto, with the map looking almost identical to Red and Blue. There are a ton of great new features, and the fun factor is through the roof, even for an old game. This generation took the already popular Pokemon franchise and skyrocketed it to Nintendo's best alongside Mario and Zelda.

column6: LEGO Lord of the Rings
column13: The 1990s called - they want their CD-ROM based copy protection back.
column14:
I'm sure the game is good enough, but I bought this to play (while traveling) on my Surface Pro 3, thinking I'd install it from a USB DVD drive, and then play it from the full install.
Sadly, this uses a "copy protection" that requires the DVD always be present, hence the game is unplayable on my target device. Found this out when I took out my Surface Pro to reduce boredom on a long flight.
It's now installed on my laptop instead, and I play it very rarely.
There are downloadable hacks to surmount the copy protection, but I hate to install what could be malware just so I can play a game.
Seriously, I thought the game industry decided this sort of copy protection was stupid a couple of decades ago.

column6: PlayStation Silver Wired Stereo Headset
column13: Has great sound for the price, but the physical build is sub-par and will break eventually.
column14: I am qualifying this to say that my headphones broke in half and are now held together only by the cushion. I am giving this a temporary 1-star rating, as I followed my own advice in light of other people having this problem, and treated the headphones with care. Also, time has taught me that the mesh covering the speakers can become rather uncomfortable during a long gaming session and leaves imprints on my ears. This might indicate that they are too tight on my head.  Has great sound for the price.  Granted the base is not as strong as some of the $150+ headphones, but I can hear footsteps and other subtle clues quite well.  [It is not as sturdy as some of the (much) more expensive headphones, but for $25, I did not expect it to be.  If you don't rip it off your head it should last].  Make sure that you rotate the mic down until it clicks, or else it will remain muted (this is an excellent feature in my opinion).  Also, the individual chat/game sound adjustment on the inline volume control is key and adds exactly what I wanted to COD Advanced warfare, as unlike some previous COD games, it does not have an option to mute all players by default.  I no longer need to individually mute all the players in a lobby.  This is really handy as you will know if you play the game.  EDIT: I compared these to a lot of other much more expensive headsets and found that these are the best for hearing footsteps and other similar audio cues. I did not bother with the warranty return/exchange process and ultimately bought a second pair. Though I was quite gentle with them, they broke anyway after a few months' use. I am really at a loss as to what rating is appropriate. I have considered just buying a third pair, as warranty repair/replace is a big hassle, but at the same time, they do not perform their function as headsets for very long, and cannot receive more than 1 star.   Add some reinforcement to the band for durability and flexibility and these would score 5 stars every singletime.

column6: Stick it to the Man PS4 - PlayStation 4
column13: Fun, fresh, and a great, novel story
column14:
Novel and fun, this is a good way to kill 6-8 hours. With a unique style and combat system, this is the definition of simple adventure. While some of the later puzzles get into the realm of merciless and hazy hardcore adventure game antics of the 90's (i.e. mix the cheez whiz and the spatula to make the nuclear detonator, obviously!), its overall straightforward and can be figured out with only 2-3 attempts.

What makes it worth it is the story, and I can't seem to figure out how to not spoil the plot except to say its about a lovable idiot whom stumbles into a mystery and psychic powers. The jokes are great, the puzzles have a new and fresh setup and feel, and you can listen to the goons for hours just for their thoughts, which are always entertaining

column6: Persona Q: Shadow of the Labyrinth
column14:
Persona Q is a GREAT game. It's not your usual Persona game, hence being a spinoff, but for a 3DS game, it is ADDICTING and fun. It's full of great music, eye-candy visuals and colors, funny and wonderous story that connects two of our favorite Persona groups together, and a great dungeon crawling + combat system. The feature of having to draw your own maps as well adds to the challenge, making it more fun and FOEs challenge your navigation strategy skills. Recommended for any JRPG/Dungeon Crawler/and/or Persona fan who has a 3DS.

The side items you get in this ridiculously cheap set are great! The 3DS LL case is hard, and comforting with a soft interior and awesome design, the classic tarot cards are a must for Persona collectors, and the Artbook and CD are great for any collection and are enjoyable. You're getting a great game, and great stuff for real cheap. Gotta 3DS? YOU MUST HAVE THIS GAME!

column6: Pulse Elite Edition Wireless Stereo Headset
column14:
I bought this headset over a year ago and so glad I did!
At first I was intimidated of all the reviews of people who said that the plastic part that holds the earcups, do crack in less than a year...
But I decided to give them a try anyway cause everyone said the sound quality was great and their only flaw was durability.
And I can tell you that if you treat them with delicacy and open them from the arc (NOT from the earcups as everybody does) every time you put them on and take them off, they're going to last years and years.
I don't know for gaming, but for music and movies the sound is just amazing!
I'd give them 5/5 on sound quality. It's hard to believe that this headset (wich was made especially for gaming) can deliver better sound and bass than a lot of the other headphones out there that were made for music, but fortunately it's true.
About comfort I'd give them 4/5 stars. They're a bit heavy and the arc gets hitted over time, but the ear cushions are big and comfy and won't hurt your ears at all, even if you use them for hours.
On durability, you MUST treat them with delicacy. Is not like they're made of birthday cake but if you treat them like any other headphones they will probably end up cracking in less than a year.
Portability 1/5. They're too big, too delicate, you can't fold them, just forget it... This were made to stay IN home.
And about the bass impact (wich was made especially for gaming), I rarely use it but when I do I use less than 10% for movies or I'll get too punchy and screw the sound. But there's really no need for it. It's like the type of thing you're almost better without it when it comes to movies and music...
So yeah there's my review. Even with all it's flaws, this headset it's worthy of every penny.
At this price range, this is just the best option for music and movies.

column6: Dark Souls
column14: I was almost sure I was going to like playing through Dark Souls. Especially since it's from the same creators of one of my favorite PS4 games Bloodborne. Unfortunately, this games is much slower and clunky. There's virtually no story elements or any memorable characters for that matter. I got bored two hours in and simply forced myself to beat this game just for the bragging rights. On a side note, Dark Souls isn't that hard (in terms of skill), it's very cheap. I mean this game often put me in circumstances where I was fighting multiple bosses or bosses and enemies at the same time. Yeah ... Now that I think about it, cheap is the only word I can use to best capture my feelings towards this game. Anywho, instead of relying on skill to beat Dark Souls (where as in Bloodborne player skill is essential),  just spam ranged attacks with a mage or archer to easily overcome most of the game. Keep in mind Dark Souls is a much slower game riddled with bugs and ever present glitches. It's a whole different experience than Bloodborne and not a memorable one at that.

column6: Xbox One 500GB Console -  Halo: The Master Chief Collection Bundle
column13: Internet system with games as a side note!
column14: I purchased the X-Box One Master Chief collection about a week ago. It was so exciting to open the X-Box One and to hook it up to the TV. That was the end of the excitement for awhile and the beginning of the horror. 1st - "Must" connect to the Internet for the initial installation of the system. No problem right! Wrong! Unable to connect to the Internet at my house. I live in the country and have satellite wifi. I had to take the Xbox One 30 miles away to my brother's house to do the setup. After connecting to DSL the Initial setup went well. 2nd- "Attempted" to download the Master Chief collection. Two days later still not downloaded. What happened? Apparently after one hour of non use during the download of the Master Chief collection, the Xbox One shut down. If the unit shuts off... No download is happening. That was the first day. Second day was spent trying to find out why the Xbox One shut down every hour. Turns out that there's a setting that shuts the unit off after one hour. You can change that setting to 6 hours or never. On the third day the download was completed. Total time to download was 13 hours not including the time wasted when the X-Box One was off. So I signed into X-Box live (required when you first play Halo and finally I could play for a few minutes. After boxing up the X-Box One I went home from my brothers house. 3rd- "Must" sign into the Xbox live. Again!!! It turns out that you must sign into X-Box live before playing the downloaded Halo game...unless you change the setting (while on x-box live) to offline. Who would have thought? So guess what....back to square one. So after getting The X-box online again (guess how) I switched the settings to offline. And finally me and my boys could play halo. So we thought. For some reason it didn't work. Once we signed out of X-Box live it happened again. We eventually figured it out and the "offline" setting took and we played Halo for hours. Excitement returned! I really love Halo! It is awesome! Almost got the sour taste out of my mouth from all those trips back and forth from my brothers house. 4th- final straw. My boys and I rented a DVD and went home to watch it on the XBox One. Yay! Not!!! After we put the disc in, it said that we Must, and I say again MUST, connect to XBox live to ..... Download an app....so we can ....watch a movie on the X-Box One. I write it that way because I...we were in disbelief. So that is where we stand now. Able to play Halo but not watch movies on the X-box One. The X-box One is an internet based system that also allows gaming. The X box One is for Internet connecting first and gaming second. If you look at the X-Box One in that light (Internet first) then I would have given it 5 stars. Instead I thought the X-box One was Gaming first with connectivity to the Internet. My mistake.  We brought a PS4 and we connected to the internet once. We even got to watch that movie on the PS4. Final analysis- X-box One and the PS 4 are totally different systems. The PS4 is for gaming first with Internet if you want. and the X-box One is for internet first with gaming second. Would I recommend someone buying the X-box One? Surprisingly, yes. But, only if they understand that the X-Box One was built around internet first gaming second. I guess that's why Microsoft went with X-box One (one system for everything) instead of X-Box 720. Maybe I'll come back and change my rating in the future. After the memories of the Internet requirements, long drives to get internet, down load times and the lack of a pre-installed app for DVD playing fades.............till then it's Halo time.  *this is an update to my original review* After having the X-box One for awhile I felt that I had to come back and update my review. Originally I gave this game system 1 star. But, now after using it for awhile I admit it's a great system. I just need better internet to be able to enjoy more of the features.

column6: Etrian Odyssey 2 Untold: The Fafnir Knight - Nintendo 3DS
column13: Nice New Installment of The Etrian Odyssey Series
column14: I received the game on it's release date but just got around to playing it yesterday. Etrian Odyessey is a dungeon crawler game but one the best aspects about it is you get to draw your own map. You paint the layouts of the floors and walls as you go along. You have special symbols to place on the map like a treasure chest symbol that changes it's appearance (when you mark a treasure chest then open it the symbol shows an open box). You can place annotations on the map marking special locations or just to make your own personal comment so you have a lot of free will in this game. You have two modes in this game a story and classic mode, the story mode is preset with already made characters and plot to go through while classic allows you to be the creator and make your own team and adventure. If you have played Persona Q then you will recognize the map system from the start. The game has several difficulty levels you can choose from, allowing you to either easily play through and enjoy the story or spend many hours grinding to get your level up so you can proceed.. so whether you enjoy playing through easily and enjoying the story or proving your skill at grinding and putting the beatdown on your enemies you won't be disappointed. If you are new to the series it won't leave you in the dark either, you can enjoy this game without having played any of the other games. The graphics and sound are impressive and the controls are simple enough so I won't go into detail on those. I basically like to leave my reviews at what I like about a game and my personal opinion on them. I'd recommend this game to anyone who's new to RPGs or who wants to give a dungeon crawler a shot. Happy Gaming to all my fellow Gamers.

column6: The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt
column13: This game is amazing, the open world story mode and side quests ...
column14: I'm not big on doing reviews but since I have played this game I felt the need too. I'm usually all about online gaming and refuse to play story modes but after seeing the previews of this game I kinda wanted to play it. So I did and it was worth every penny I spent on it. I forgot all about destiny and COD! I haven't played the previous witcher games so this was my first go at it. This game is amazing,the open world story mode and side quests will keep you busy! I followed the main story and finished the main story around level 30 not meaning too so I realized there was so much I didn't explore by following the main story line and barely doing the side quests. So if you do buy this game make sure to do all of the side quests, treasure hunts and undiscovered location as well as the main story. I would advice to do them as there is so much more to it (because i started it over again and I'm romancing triss this time) also the fact that your decision changes the outcome is awesome in this game. I saved 2 characters in my first game and starting my 2nd game I choose different and ended having a completely different outcome!!! My only beef is the long loading time, roach the horse can pop up in the most awkward places and the lighting candles and torches around stuff makes you wana pull your hair out, I mean you could be running for your life and he wants to stop and light a candle because pressing the run button also lights fires!! So I haven't been doing any online gaming since I bought this game. This is one of my favorite games even though I rarely play RPG games.

column6: God of War Collection - PlayStation Vita
column13: If you like action game with Gore and Greek history this is ...
column14:
If you like action game with Gore and Greek history this is your game.
It comes with God of War 1 and 2 and cost $19.99 is Great deal if you never play this game.

Play style- Like Devil May Cry, Oni musha with Hard core Gore with Adult content added.
Third person action you play as Kratos and two button to attack( Light and Heavy attack) Jump, Guard, and special attack. New function with Vita is that it has touch censer in the back so it will make you touch it when you open treasure box,to talk to person or light object you see in the screen. This might be frustrating to do since some times it recognize even you were not mentioning to do by holding the touch censer part, but once you get the game play it doesn't disturbed you since you will be into the story and action which is lot of fun.
Play time- I beat it in 7 hours for God of War and 9 hours of God of War 2 I like to full up all the weapon and health as possible before the last boss so I took lot of time in the game. If you try just beating the game, maybe you can beat the game much faster.
Game graphic and sound- Graphic is not great and old graphic looking compare to modern game since it was made doing PS 2 era but It is in HD remaster and I did not feel really old with the graphic. Sound is very clear and nice with the Movie Mummy like music.

Over All- If you haven't play this game and you are looking for action game, you must have this game. I wish they will release God of War 3 and Ascension for PS Vita to complete the God of War series.

column6: PDP AG7 True Wireless Headset for Xbox One
column13: Wireless is the only way to go
column14:
This headset is truly unique. Ready to use right out of the box since it is paired at the factory. No need to be pushing buttons and dealing with pairing it to your game console. Just plug in the USB transmitter into our XBox One, turn on your PDF AfterGlow Headset and you are ready to go.

Has a wireless frequency of 2.4GHz. Claims to have a range of 40 feet but I attempted to go from my bedroom to the kitchen which is about 15 feet and the chat was choppy and came in and out. However, the battery life of 16 hours is true. I am able to get anywhere from 15-16 hours of battery life from one charge. To get longer life of your battery, turn off the headset glow feature on the headphones, this will conserve some battery power. I however love the glow! They take about 3 hours to fully charge back to life.

In regards to ear fatigue, they are adjustable but might be a little snug if you have a larger than average sized head. The padding on the top of the headset and over the ear cups are very well cushioned. After a couple of hours of play my ears were not uncomfortable or itchy.

More and more headsets are going towards this type of microphone - flexible and retractable types. This one is a longer than ones I have tried before but it seems this type always have problems. I got complaints that I was not able to be heard some of the time. It is more like cellphone quality conversation where you hear from one ear. I sounded muffled and unclear. However, it could also be my internet connection.

The power and mute is controlled by a large button on the cup. There are two modes that are controlled by mode button located on the headset. It controls basic audio and bass-boost modes, There are light indicators at the end of the mic to let you know what mode you are in.

In regards to game audio, this is where does the best. I don't place the volume on high where my ears will be ringing after playing games. I prefer a comfortable level where I can clearly hear the game and feel like I am inside the game action but still be aware of my surroundings. The AG7 does just that with crisp sounds and deep tones.

Besides the cool looks and great game audio, I love how I don't have to use that PITA XBox One headset game adapter on my controller. Using that thing drove me nuts because I kept bending the cable since I would set the controller on my stomach while playing. And I don't even want to go into trying to control the audio with that adapter.

Even though it is wireless, it can be used with MP3 players or mobile devices using the audio-in jack cable.prefer a comfortable level where I can clearly hear the game and feel like I am inside the game action but still be aware of my surroundings. The AG7 does just that with crisp sounds and deep tones.

Besides the cool looks and great game audio, I love how I don't have to use that PITA XBox One headset game adapter on my controller. Even though it is wireless, it can be used with MP3 players or mobile devices using the audio-in jack cable.

column6: Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare
column14:
This is a downright awful game. The single player is entirely predictable. I can't think of another game where you work for a PMC and the find out they're the bad guys all along (Army of Two, HAWX off the top of my head).
The multiplayer has no community management, Sledgehammer refuses to update the PS3 version of this game. The maps are too small for the exo abilities. The weapons in multiplayer are incredibly unbalanced, and it doesn't help that the hit detection is broken.

I would only recommend this if you can find it used or on sale. I'm so happy I didn't pay the full price for this.

Pros:
Kevin Spacey
Somewhat entertaining story

Cons:
Amateur developer
Unbalanced and broken multiplayer
Multiplayer lobbys filled with hackers
No community management from developer or publisher
No support from developer or publisher
Several severe bugs in single player and multiplayer, to the point of hard reboot

column6: XCOM: Enemy Within
column14:
The only elements I enjoyed about this game is that the gameplay mechanics is similar to the Mass Effect series (note that I said similar, not the same). XCom Declassified is a third person, cover- based shooter. You do have squadmates what you issue orders to. The combat is played in real-time (unlike previous XComs which were turn-based strategy games). There is a radial wheel which lets you choose different dialog choices when speaking to Npcs; in certain segments of the game.

The dialog wheel and character level up system lend it an RPG aspect similar to ME, though here in XCom, it rather limited. And that limitation is by the very fact that the dialog choices doesn't affect the storyline or the character interactions.

Though I won't go into the generic story about aliens attacking earth. You are sent into different parts of the USA to destroy, retrieve or explore alien infested areas. Before doing so however, you can select sqaudmates and outfit them with weapons and equipement. There are different classes of squadmates which have their own weapon specialization and abilities.

The requisitory sniper, shotgunner, smgs etc are there and each class has an abilty unique to them. Some have to abilty to cloak, lay down automated laser turrets, land mines, abililties to distract l, levitate alien enemies are also there (as are self healing and critical hits.)

The ME influnces and gameplay mechanics are prevalent, but their exectutions are poorly implemented in XCom. During the cover and shoot actions your character feels a bit unresponsive and sometimes require that you try to get cover behind walls or objects multiple times. The same thing occurs when rolling on ground to reach a cover point or dodge-roll.

When you face off aliens in combat you can slow down time to issue specific orders to squadmates and to activate their individual special abilities (which are limited to a brief cooling period before being able to activate them again).

Your A.I. squadmates can engage enemies of there own voilition, but the biggest problem is that they are incredibly stupid. They will run into your line of fire, run out into the open to get perforated by enemy fire. If your squadmates get wounded you have a limited amount of time to heal them before they die. Their death is permanent and well deserved because their stupidity is a severe impedance and takes away all enjoyment of this game.

Without any multiplayer or co-op feature, the novelty and replay value of XCom declassified is near zero and can barely justify a purchase even from the bargain bin.

Pros:
+cover shoot mechanics similar to Mass Effect
+special abilities

Cons:
-incredibly stupid A.I.
-unresponsive controls
-boring story
-linear missions
-linear dialog which makes no difference to the story
-boring wave after wave of enemies
-aliens are over-powered for a big portion of the game
-not worth more than $5.00 dollars

column14:
This and Destiny are my favorite Xbox 360 games ever! Skyrim is the ultimte RPG/Fantasy and is filled with multiple quests and storylines roughout the entire game and not just the main camapign questline. Skyrim can be extremely addicting at times. For example when I had spent about three hours on a quest, two new ones popped right up for me to do. All in all I give this game a 5/5 star review. The graphics in this game are top notch for 2012 standards. Skyrim may have a bit of outdated graphics but it makes up for it in the amazing gameplay and overall feel of the game. Even if you're not into RPG or Fantasy type games, you will definitly enjoy Skyrim. All in all this game easily deserves well more than 5 stars, but the maximum rating that I can give it is only 5 stars :)
In conclusion, this is a great RPG/Fantasy game and just a great game in general and I think that it is easily (along with Destiny) the best Xbox 360 game ever!
