column6: Thrustmaster T500RS Racing Wheel - Playstation 3
column13: Amazing but costly. Can need some maintenance.
column14:
I bought this steering wheel while in France (Thrustmaster is a French company, previously called Guillemot and specialized in making joysticks) back in December 2012. I have been using it ever since. It is a wonderful piece of hardware. I previously owned a Logitech G27 and before that the Microsoft side winder or something like that. Every time, my driving scores have improved with the upgrades.

What's to like:
- Serious hardware with 3 motors and amazing quality. The pedals are made of metal alloy and extremely heavy and sturdy. The resistance of the pedals is very good and simulate those of a real car.
- You can set the pedals two ways, rF1 and GT depending on your preference or room available.
- The pedals are very heavy and will stay put when you drive, unlike other plastic ones that constantly slide on carpet.
- The driving sensation is very good and my driving performance increased when compared to Logitech.
- Excellent and strong force feedback. This thing set to the maximum FFB will get your arms sore after a while.
- Stay put when attached to your desk or table and placement is not as limited as the Logitech wheels.

What I like much less:
- I thought I had bricked it twice while upgrading the firmware. There are some workarounds to get it back to life that are not too difficult to follow. I am by the way using it with a PC, not with a console.
- Price is high.
- No stick shift attached. You can still use the manual gears but you will have to use the pads behind the wheel. You can buy a very good one but for another 150 bucks...
- Fan can get loud at times.

column6: PlayStation 4 500GB Console [Old Model]
column14:
This is the console generation where Sony got it's mojo back. During the last generation, it felt like Sony was largely playing catch up with the features of Xbox Live and the Xbox in general. The PS4 has eliminated the gap and shot slightly ahead in terms of raw technical specs. Virtually gone is the move controller and any integration with motion control. This console focuses on gaming and it largely succeeds.

Pros:
1. Big step up in graphics from the PS3.
2. Overall better specs with a 500gb hard drive to handle increasingly chunkier game updates and downloads.
3. The Playstation Network is finally ready for prime time. (even if it's frequently getting attacked)
4. New controller adds functionality through slight evolution.
5. Integrated movie capture mode that allows you to save the last 15 minutes of game play with the push of 2 buttons.
6. Integration has been added to share your accomplishments via social media like Facebook and YouTube.
7. Ever increasing game library.

Cons:
1. Hard drive could be bigger.
2. There is no way to be online without all of your PSN friends seeing your online status.
3. No backward compatibility with PS3 games.

I would highly recommend this game console.

column6: Metal Gear Solid: The Legacy Collection
column14: Absolutely worth the price of admission; The Legacy Collection was a great way to play through the main series in anticipation of MGSV. These games give you a truckload of equipment, and it's up to you to figure out all the crazy tricks and secrets you can get with them. The stealth gameplay is challenging, but immensely rewarding - sneaking past a row of guards is ten times as satisfying compared to gunning them down one by one. The collection skips a few games in the series, including AC!D and Portable Ops, but they aren't important to the story so I suppose it's fine. Overall, the Metal Gear series isn't one you should miss, even if action games aren't your thing.

column6: NHL 14
column14: I was getting a little bored of NHL 13, so I just decided to upgrade a little. It is so much different than '13. First of all, there is so much good about this game, but there are downsides to it. I'll start with the good. The hitting, fighting, and overall gameplay is much improved. I'm glad they ditched the first person fighting, but third person is kinda confusing at first. The hits and checks feel like I'm in my screen playing. There are other great things to the game, but I'll start going to the cons. The scoring is so strange. For example I was playing earlier and there would be this one spot I would shoot and score over half of the time. Anyways, the cpu was playing poorly and the score was 3-8 at the end of the second period. I played even harder in the third, and for however reason, they found ways around and made it 8-8 with less than ten seconds left. They lugged it forward and magically there was the opponent in front of my goal who scored with 1.2 seconds left on the clock. Does it get anymore fixed to win then that? I wanted to break the disc! I guess they were trying to give me a game, but come on. Another thing is the commentary. It sounds like a repeat of NHL 13 with a few new lines thrown in there. I don't know if it's just me, but the commentators sounded like they were bored out of their minds! They also needed to do work on the crowd! When I was playing the other day, I scored on the opponent and my home crowd sat and booed me! It seems like it's accuracy was off. When they do get "excited", it sounds like they're getting add thrilled as being on a merry-go-round. But when I score, they usually go insane like there's a riot, so I get confused on what's happening every once and a while. I do think though that the graphics are also better by quite a bit compared to '13. Another weird thing I noticed that was probably an EA Sports screw-up is when I go into my settings to play as the goalie, it will say "Goalie Mode On" when I'm not on that mode, and "Goalie Mode Off" when I activate it. It was the complete opposite in NHL 13. They most likely messed up the text on it. One last thing, when I poke check or steal the puck and it's still there on the ice, the opponent usually ends up getting it back due to my guy not getting it when I'm right in front of it. Overall though, this was a great buy and a long shot better than NHL 13. Hope this helps!on that mode, and "Goalie Mode Off" when I activate it. It was the complete opposite in NHL 13. They most likely messed up the text on it. One last thing, when I poke check or steal the puck and it's still there on the ice, the opponent usually ends up getting it back due to my guy not getting it when I'm right in front of it. Overall though, this was a great buy and a long shot better than NHL 13. Hope this helps!

column6: Kingdom Hearts Re:coded
column14:
Ugh. Where to begin with this game?

Re:coded is, by far, the weakest entry in the Kingdom Hearts series. It started as a mobile game and quite frankly, it shows. The worlds are incredibly repetitive. The level design is incredibly weak in a series with fairly mediocre level design. The story is laughable and does not really tie in to the main story at all except towards the end. There's a lot of extra content but most of it involves replaying levels and I'm not sure why anyone would want to do that.

Assuming you have played any Kingdom Hearts game before, this game technically takes place almost right after KH2. The story begins with Mickey, Donald, Goofy, and Jiminy Cricket attempting to access Jiminy's first journal by digitizing it. Of course, it turns out that the whole thing is full of bugs and thus employ DataSora (i.e. the Sora from the journal) to delete them. Thus, Sora goes from familiar world to familiar world destroying bugs. Frankly, the story is laughably thin and fails to do much more than harp on notes already introduced in previous installments even as it tries to introduce some level of interest.

The level design, with a few exceptions, is literally just older maps with a bunch of blocks (or "blox") thrown on top. The result is fairly ugly (which is the point I suppose) and also manages to suck out any of the charm that the game might possess by virtue of its Disney source material. And of course, the worlds repeat themselves frequently just to make it through the default story; and of course the game wants you to repeat them even more to get 100% which is absolutely infuriating. And who had the bright idea to, towards the end of the game, start replacing the Heartless with poorly designed Blox Spider monsters? The game does introduce one new environment in the form of system servers. Throughout the game, Sora is called upon to enter into digital holes in the datascape to fix bugs, which requires the completion of minilevels. These are also fairly frustrating in their repetition and annoying platforming sections.

Many of the boss battles have been replaced by quasi-mini games, such as side-scrolling, shoot em ups, and turn-based RPGs. Compared to the rest of the game, these are actually pretty fun. The actual gameplay itself feels pretty good for a console, especially compared to the clunky interface and controls of Days. However, that is not enough to save this game, though it is enough for me to grant it two instead of one star.

Do yourself a favor and watch the cutscenes or something. It is not worth purchasing and definitely does not stand alone as a game worth playing in any capacity, even for the die-hard KH fan.

column6: Lost Dimension
column13: Expect an easy game that doesn't stick out from the crowd
column14:
Between this and valkyria chronicles, the latter will do everything better than this game can, so I highly suggest playing VC for a quality time instead of this vita port.

Lost dimension is simply put an easy game with an easy storyline and in the event that you actually have trouble with the game you can buy levels and money/exp bonuses. The game starts you off in battle after finishing one of the very few (low budget) animated cuticles and surprise surprise everyone is amnesiac and can't remember what they were doing moments prior after wiping out the mobs in the tutorial fight they meet the antagonist "the end" after explaining the pillar (where the game mainly takes place) to the protagonists he vanishes.

After finishing quests to level up characters and gain currency known as "EN (energy)" you can chat with the other characters to bond with them which besides them assisting you (no romance in this game either to my knowledge so don't bother expecting to get it in with nagi, himeno or mana) doesn't do much much else besides get the "true ending" (more on that later,) the main gimmick in this game is the "traitor system" which in a nutshell means that someone (at most 3) will betray you at the end of the game, the only thing that does though is make you fight them before the boss which isn't that tough, I myself kept himeno up till the end of the game and had to fight her although It didn't even take a turn to wipe the floor with her, if you guess all 3 or 4 times correctly during judgment then you won't have to fight them at all, note that figuring out who the traitors are does take a bit of logic to figure out.

Essentially the game repeats from there, you bond with characters, figure out who the traitor is and kill them, progress through levels and upgrade equipment till you reach the top of the tower where you fight the final boss and congrats you beat the game, or maybe not!

If youdidn't bond with everyone then you get the "normal ending" where you defeat the end but are left at a cliff hanger.

Now I could play through the whole game again (new game plus, started at the beginning at lvl 6 instead of lvl, that's all I saw before I stopped posting) and get a better grasp of the story but honestly I couldn't care less to do so and won't put forth the effort because in the end I just don't care, in the beginning I was enjoying the game and didn't even have high expectations but those started falling near the end of the game, honestly valkyria chronicles is far better than this vita port clone (that has a stuttering and crashing problem) so you should save your money and buy VC for only $18 to get the physical version, you'll be in for a much better time.

For anyone wondering there is no multiplayer in this game and you should really get this game on vita I can't say with 100% guarantee but I'm pretty sure the only difference between the PS3 and PSV versions is the resolution, this game Is simply far more suited to a handheld over a console.

Tl;dr buy Valkyria Chronicles instead of this over priced lower quality clone. (about $18)

column13: Mouse works well, instructions slightly unclear, EagleTec's website doesn't work on Chrome.
column14:
I have mixed feelings about this product and company, but for a $7 wireless mouse, I really can't complain. So many features for such a low price.

Eagletec packaged the mouse very nicely in a perfect sized box, but their "instructions" have some room for improvement. All it does is direct you to their website in a few different languages. Their website wouldn't load on Chrome, but I was able to bring it up on Safari.

When I first opened the box, I was impressed with the materials the mouse was made with. It's not as great as the Apple "Magic" mouse I use at work, but the price difference reflects this. Performance wise though, this mouse is better. Very responsive and the mouse fits in my hand nicely. I love that the scrolling speed can be changed with the simple push of a button.

I had a little trouble getting the battery to fit correctly at first. I had it orientated correctly, so the lights on the mouse lit up, but the battery needed to be *clicked* in to make the mouse track movements. Not sure if this is the case for everyone, but it is something to keep an eye on as had I not bumped the battery when I was trying to take it out I would have tried to return it. Now it works flawlessly, no complaints.

column6: Rocksmith 2014
column13: Ordered it twice, neither one worked
column14: The game loads fine, but after that, it didn't work.  So we returned it, ordered a new one, and the same exact thing happened.  After the game loads, it walks you through the steps to begin using it.  You plug the cord into your guitar which is plugged into the PS4 console.  Then the narrator tells you to strum your guitar loud until the game picks it up or recognizes it or whatever.  But the game never does recognize the guitar or do anything at all after that point.  My son strummed his guitar til his fingers were sore, and the game did nothing.  I can see one game being defective, but two?  We trouble-shot over the phone with Rocksmith, who said there was no issues with the type of guitar we were using.  They suggested trying it on someone elses PS4, but everyone near us uses a different gaming console.  Frustrating.  Will have to get a refund and not buy again.

column14: Update: My defense is still weak. I use Real Madrid. The game is well made, except for defense. It's such a huge mistake on EAs behalf. But it's still the best game out there now. Hopefully will be fixed in the 2016 version   After a week of playing FIFA 15, i hate it. I've moved up to 4th division in this span, but hate the defense. EA forgot to make defending more realistic. Shooting and scoring from 3/4 length and scoring is unreal. Keepers can't grab on to the ball, even on soft shots. Double teams are flawed. Manual defense is extremely cumbersome and inconsistent. In the effort to make the game more realistic, EA forgot about DEFENSE. I'm a lifelong soccer player and played college ball. So, I know soccer. The dribbling is okay, keepers are terrible. But defense was such an after thought that I can't give any good ratings to this game because defense is also part of the game. A half baked game isn't good enough.

I REALLY liked the game, not the best game I've ever played, but it has descent story, graphics, playthrough, voice acting etc...
The idea of weapon switching is both annoying and clever, depending on how you look at it :)
I was not a huge fan of switching the character you control so many times during the game.. I feel it removes from immersion, so 2 characters would probably have been enough but it's ok I guess.
My issues are the length of the game, it's super short, which is too bad since it's pretty good!
On this, I have less issues with a game like Overkill being so short, because the shooting-at-monsters part is really fun, but in DSE, the shooting part is not THAT fun, so it's not like I'd replay it over and over to shoot more monsters... On that topic, if all you want is a fun rail game, this is probably not it.

And finally the ending. There is pretty much only what seems to be a trailer for the following game (DS1) and we don't get to learn anything... I know this is a prequel, but it should stand on its own, which it does pretty well till the ending. True now I want to play DS1, but it's on a different platform.. and it'll be a different genre...

TLDR: Great game for a few hours, but don't spend too much on it thinking you'll be playing 100+ hours...

column6: Collective Minds Chatboost Chat Pad with Battery Pack
column13: The only Keyboard for your controller that actually works.
column14:
I've been through a couple terrible but similar keyboards and I cannot find a serious flaw with this one. Some have said the battery recharge function doesn't work, but I'm here to tell you on mine it very much does. I agree with some of the complaints that the function buttons are weirdly placed but this is something you get used to over time, and it's still faster than typing with your joystick. The weight doesn't affect my gaming, in fact I find it better than a bare controller, keeping the weight evenly distributed, instead of front heavy (something you won't even notice till you play with, and then without this for a while). The light up function is nice and, so far, the battery power is great. I've yet to have this die while playing a couple days in a row, and ended up recharging it anyways after a while because...why not? The recharge function works on my controller and has actually fully recharged the controller, while still being useable as a typing apparatus, and continued to work long after the controller was fully charged. The little ring that goes around the PS button does NOT hinder the access to that button in any way, and fits around it cleanly. If it affects anything at all, I would say it does block the speaker on the controller, but the only reason that is a problem is because sometimes I will put my thumb over the speaker, so it doesn't tell another player what I'm up to (this is mostly a problem in GTA when you're calling a mugger or Maryweather on someone and your headset microphone can hear it because it's so close to the controller speaker). With that ring around the PS button, I can't put my thumb cleanly over it, and my friends know when I'm pranking them with a mugger attack. Heh. On the plus side, however, that ring has greatly decreased the number of times my thumb has slipped off the joystick and hit the PS button in a frantic moment.

If there is one true complaint I have, and to some this may be a big one, is that I personally like to use my Playstation Camera's microphone a lot. To either command the PS4 or talk to other players without having to wear headgear. Because of this keyboard's pass through jack that allows you to still plug in a headset, the plug on the keyboard activates the PS4's headset detection, and disengages the microphone on the camera. I have not found a work around for this and sometimes find it frustrating. If you're playing a game at all that requires the camera, you'll want to take this off (or grab another controller), or plug in a headset. The headsets work great with it, but for someone like me who doesn't like to be tethered to my controller or have something in my ear when I'm casually gaming, this can be a major flaw. I almost removed a star for this problem, since for me it's a rather big deal, but being that most players use headsets and HATE the camera speakerphone option, this isn't a complaint many of you will have. I also have NOT tried a bluetooth headset in conjunction with this, but that's because I hate bluetooth headsets due to the need to recharge them far too often. Another small complaint is that the initial charge is rather brutally lengthy, I think it said 7 hours, but this isn't so bad as long as you leave it charging overnight while the PS4 is on sleep mode, or charging it while playing all day with another controller. I also don't recommend taking this on or off frequently as it fits snug, and could break or scratch the controller with constant attaching and detaching, but being that I have several controllers already, it's easy to just leave it on one, and grab that controller if I feel I will ever need it.

Any other flaws aside I could note above may not be worth mentioning if you really need a keyboard for your controller, because this is the ONLY one that I've found that works out of the very limited selection out there, and works great for what it's supposed to do. If you're someone that for whatever reason will absolutely need a keyboard with quick access and not a separate unit from your controller, this is possibly your only option and, like me, you'll forgive the flaws. I've been using it for a couple weeks now and besides the few nit-picks I've mentioned, I have had zero issues that seriously affect my gaming experience. Is it a necessity? No. Will you regret buying this? No. So if you have the money, pick it up, if anything as an optional accessory as it is extremely handy in games with text based puzzles or functions, most notably the GTA Online text message function, or character creator games with name inputs.ly need a keyboard with quick access and not a separate unit from your controller, this is possibly your only option and, like me, you'll forgive the flaws. column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column13: Not the MMO I wanted to play
column14:
You know something is amiss when your product price drops $20 a month after your pre-order arrives. And while I resisted reading up on this game before buying it, this experience has made me question if future Elder Scrolls games will be instant buy like they have been in the past, I certainly will not be buying another MMO from Zenimax. I can speak from the experience that I have put in enough time to have two veteran ranked characters and have completed the Domain campaign with them both.

I have played as both a vampire and werewolf, and I'm not impressed with either, they feel tacked on in my opinion. Why not have a normal infection rate of 0.0001% rather than having players spawn camping for hours at a time? This would also make player-to-player infection more valuable.

All in all, the main game is serviceable with my main gripe being that each area is essentially walking you up levels. Battles with mobs are typically easy, repeatable, and tends to get boring. You don't seem to gather much experience for leveling just battling, it seems you'll level up more by completing quests. The line of sight for mobs is laughable, you can get within about 5 feet of their face before they're alerted. The only times I've been defeated by mobs is when I've been outnumbered 4:1 or worse, which your battles are staged around 2 or 3 to 1. There aren't very many surprises either, no random high trophy hunts to have (like the leader of a wolf pack for example). However, there are seemingly random portals that spawn 5-6 daedric mobs, but they're always in the same places on the map.

Things that made both Oblivion and Skyrim fun have been removed. Things like schools of magic, the assassins and thieves guilds (though you can steal and fence items), and a feeling of sheer scope of the world. In their places are (more or less) sliced-up neatly leveled areas, awkwardly designed classes, and shoehorned alliances for the sake of story. You will find out that your quest is being completed at the same times as others are doing them, too. And if you're up against a quest boss, and someone else kills it, guess what? You're done too! Without the challenge of fighting it, and if you didn't damage it, you lost out on their loot, too.

Crafting is a rub because you really don't have to craft anything to be successful in the campaigns. I actually sold all my materials for everything below rank 46-50 since it was just taking up space in my bank. The research function is arbitrarily long for no reason except to make it seem like you're actually getting more skilled. It takes several (or more days) for one piece once several attributes are already done, but you can craft an entire set of metal armor or cook a whole meal in mere seconds.

I actually had to give up on learning enchanting because of the sheer time sink required for a marginal benefit over what you can find in the wild. Potions aren't really required to learn, as they're less effective than healing abilities, and food/drinks are also plentiful from drops.

Playing PvP actually irked me enough to cancel my subscription. If you aren't at least veteran rank 8 by now, you won't be effective at all, even though you can join in as low as player rank 10 (or 48 levels lower). I don't understand this, as wild mobs are veteran rank 12, no less, no more. I had a hard time understanding why Cyrodiil was is huge and wide open while the campaigns felt cramped and overpopulated. You can't PvP unless you're in Cyrodiil, no duels, no bounties, no guild wars. And instead of helping newer players enter the PvP area, they rewarded people who play the game more with scaled-up armor and stats and even champion points. Also, there are no trophies for PvP, no body looting for any sort, and really no reason to fight for anything other than to fight for castles on the map or dumbed down elder scrolls. Why not have a reason to fight for one of the cities? Why arethere no NPC mercenaries from the towns who'd fight for whoever pays them the most? Why does this Elder Scroll give me only 2% defense boost, but can alter the flow of time in Skyrim? Less than inspired in this gamers opinion.

Issues I see (and some rants): People aren't really grouping for dungeons, and they're scaled against one person attempts. Why not just scale down your rewards instead? Better loot for better groups.
People don't group for campaigns, since they're too easy to not require them. Why not have mob hunts that require grouping?
Being a one person force in Cyrodiil is suicide, unless you're a veteran rank 14 kiting about a dozen people, because youre stats are scaled so high.
Why is there a bounty system, but players can't posse up to hunt you?
Every stolen item is priced at 30.
I got the customer service rep to agree with me that Coldharbour siege items are game breakers, as they don't have either a displayed projectile or impact area like all the others do.
No auction house, and guild traders seem to be heavily overpriced.
A distinct lack of legendary gear before veteran ranks.

There's more, but this is running a bit long...

column6: Donop Black Pc Wireless Controller Gaming USB Receiver Adapter for Pc Xbox 360
column13: Works great, once you get the right drivers...
column14:
Worked great on my computer after I did some extra steps. I'm running Windows 7 64bit. It wouldn't connect to my controller initially, and my computer wouldn't recognize it, but I used this method I found online and it worked like a charm! Just do a Google search for "360 wireless receiver not connecting controller" and check out the first result.

-Right click on Computer
-Go to Properties
-Click on Device Manager
-Right click on the Unidentified Device
-Go to Properties
-Go to the Drive tab
-Click on Update Driver
-Click on "Browse my computer for driver software"
-Click on "Let me pick from a list of device drivers on my computer"
-Choose "Microsoft Common Controller for Window Class"
-Choose "Xbox 360 Wireless Receiver for Windows Version: 2.1.0.1349 [8/13/2009]"
-Click Yes on Update Driver Warning

That's it. Happy gaming!

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column14:
I never post on amazon, but I just had to on this.
Rent before you throw your hard earned money to Bethesda.
I wanted to like this .... really really wanted to like this, but in the end ... ill be waiting for fallout to fill that RPG need.

Probs
1) Gotta love going on a quest only to have the dungeon mostly cleared by the 30 other people who got there just a little before you did. No more slow methodical approach ... nope run in blazing cause odds are, youll be lucky to get a couple hits in before the boss goes down. Stategy element ... gone. Sense of accomplishment ... gone. Wanting to play in your own style ... gone. It frickin sucks !!!!!!! I like to go in stealthy, picking guys away ... nope, they're either all dead or with 5 people all running in to claim the kill, you may as well rush in as well or else you're shooting dead corpses pretending you killed em just the same

2) So may missions of go to A, go to B, report back to A, go to C etc. You can spend hours doing nothing but errands.
3) Storyline so drab (along with #2 above) that when a decision point came along, I was so bored, lost and couldn't care less.
4) Enemies respawn quickly at the same point every time. No mystery. No clearing a room and being able to run back to safety (no need with #1 above) or just sitting tinkering with equipment (or going to the bathroom / fridge) over a dead body only to have his double reappear in his place and start attacking you
5) They've complicated things greatly from Skyrim.

At least in destiny, which shares some of this, they limit the amount of people in an area to a much greater extent, and when your on a mission, its just you (and your group) and the others vanish. You clear a room the way you want and progress without myriads of other people battling you for kills or 10 of you placing a stone emblem on the same pedestal, all doing the exact same mission at the same time in chaotic semi-unison and fighting over treasure.

in a word its an MMO gone mad. The solo element of Skryim blows.

Boring, tedious and unrewarding. You only keep playing hoping it gets better or you'll adjust .... it doesn't and you wont.

oh ... and a ridiculous cap on what you can carry, restricted fast travel (like the witcher) ... just other peeves of mine.

Hard to find a redeeming quality. Rent for a day and see if once your in the game play even just a few hours, if this mass hysteria works for you before you buy.

Ill say this ... I had no server issues on PS4 with these guys ... there was at least that.

but man ... this was the biggest disappointment I've had in gaming in a very long time . Wish I could get my $50 back.

column6: The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt
column13: Could this be the best CRPG ever made?
column14:
The Witcher 3, quite simply, exceeded all of my expectations and now stands in my mind as one of the best CRPGs I have ever played, if not the best. Having played and enjoyed the other two Witcher games, I expected a solid RPG experience with an interesting story and some memorable characters. What I did not expect was to be drawn so deeply into a beautifully and painstakingly crafted world for dozens upon dozens of hours.

Every aspect of the Witcher 3 is simply amazing. The story is compelling. The characters are interesting and memorable. Even the smallest side-quests are given life and meaning. The world is beautiful, detailed, and feels like a living place. Combat is solid, and there is a very robust crafting system. And, most interesting, the choices the player is required to make are difficult, weighty, and often have consequences that do not become apparent until many hours letter. In fact, I enjoyed this game so much that I read each of the Witcher novels and short story collections, all of which only added to my enjoyment of the game and put some of the characters and events in context.

Move over Skyrim, Baldur's Gate II, Dragon Age. The Witcher 3 has raised the bar.

As an aside, the game runs flawlessly (60+ fps) on my PC, which is an i5 with GeForce 970GT, with most settings on Ultra but Nvidia Hairworks off. I have encountered very few bugs, though the game did crash to my desktop a couple of times (changing from Fullscreen to Windowed mode seemed to fix that issue).

column6: F1 2015 - Parent
column14: I'll start off by saying that I respect everyone's opinions on this game. To each their own. Games are often highly subjective. But, I don't understand why some are saying this is a terrible game. I'll just share a few of my thoughts about it.  First, the graphics aren't bad. They aren't great though. They're somewhere in between. The weather effects are nice and the car models are well done. Some of tracks look great (Monaco for example), but some look bland (Spa and Silverstone for example). But when concentrating on racing it doesn't really matter too much. The character models are ok. You can tell who is who by looking at them. But they're not anything to write home about. Again, they're adequate.  The presentation is the biggest disappointment for me. They advertised it like it was going to be like a live broadcast. It's not even close and doesn't capture the atmosphere of a Formula 1 race. It does better than previous installments. But there's a lot more work to be done.  I'm fine with the game modes. As a person that doesn't like playing any kind of licensed sports games as my own created character, I like the new championship mode. I've been wanting to race as actual drivers for awhile. It feels more authentic for me. Personally, I don't like creating characters and using them. But I can see how that's a huge deal to some.  It's lacking a little bit in the settings for races. I'd like to be able to choose an exact number of laps per race. Some choices feel too short, while the next option feels too lengthy sometimes. I would like to able to have a full practice session, 3 session qualifying, but then have a shorter race if I choose to. I don't know if you can change that. If you can, I haven't found it yet. Basically, I love being able to have the 3 session qualifying, but don't want to have to do a full race to do it. At least not all the time. The settings for the cars seem to be adequate enough for my taste. Although, diehard purests may want more. I don't use any of the assists. So I can't speak towards that.  The handling seems to be fine to me. I find it better and more responsive than previous years. Although, it could be refined some. Especially for controller use. (Yes, some people still prefer a controller. Especially those of us not wanting to drop hundreds of dollars on a steering wheel and setup.)  The sound is what you would expect. Everything seems in order there. Nothing to complain about other than the commentary before the races is a little dull. And when it is supposed to be exciting, it seems to try too hard.  Final thoughts: As a huge F1 fan that watches all the races, I'm giving this a solid 4 stars. I like the ability to play as my favorite drivers. This isn't the huge step forward that Codemasters said it would be. Or even that it should have been. But I think it's an improvement and a step in the right direction. I'd also like to see the classic mode return.

column6: TIGER & BUNNY aired Jack! [Japan Import]
column13: even if you don't have a good grasp on the Japanese language
column14:
To start off, even if you don't have a good grasp on the Japanese language, you can still play this game without much trouble. The tutorials are complete with pictures, and if you've ever seen the anime you'll know exactly what's happening in the plot when it happens.

This game's mostly about the missions. You play as Tiger, and your goals are pretty much the same as they are in the TV series; get the bad guy, save the victims, impress the audience, and send a shout-out to your sponsors all within five minutes to earn points and boost your Hero Rank. It's a good ol' beat 'em up is what it is, son. Each map I've played so far has been different, with lots of little nooks and crannies to explore. There are various "happening" points that allow you to keep your viewers entertained while you scramble after the suspects, and you actually have some incentive to get them. People become less impressed with what you've got to show the longer you walk around or the more hits you take. As another feature, you can get one of the other heroes to cut in for you and raise your audience rating or take some damage for you. This is REALLY helpful during boss battles.

(Side note: This isn't really important, but they included a point reduction for when you break public property in battle. I just thought it was cool that they paid so much attention to detail.)

The only real complaint I have is that the camera can be dizzying, and the controls flip whenever it changes. It's frustrating, but it's easy to look over.

As for the shipment, I ordered it new without expediting it. It arrived in about 20 days, which I think is a perfectly reasonable amount of time for imports. It came in perfect condition. Included with the manual are a little sticker sheet with all the characters and a Barnaby card with a serial code on the back.

In short, it's pretty much as close to being a real anime superhero that you'll ever get. It's really addicting, and I totally recommend it to anyone that likes T&B.ddicting, and I totally recommend it to anyone that likes T&B.

column6: Ortz PS4 Vertical Stand with Cooling Fan - Controller Charging Station with Dual Charger
column14:
This stand is nice and all (I actually like how sleek the design is), but I bought it primarily for the cooling systemthe fans. At the end of the day, it's all about the function (and I think most customers would agree). The PS4 is notorious for getting very hot very fast (sometimes within the first 30 minutes of gameplay), so I believed this stand would solve that. The product totes that the stand has "powerful" fans that will keep your PS4 cool, which is, of course, entirely false. There are only two fans (one in the front and one in the back, at least four inches apartterrible placement) and they spin so slowly that they barely provide any cooling. Also, once the PS4 is positioned on the stand, the fans are trapped underneath it, so there is no ventilation. If anything, the fans will just keep pushing the hot air back into your system (because, if you didn't know, the cooling vents on the PS4 are ON THE SIDES, and the stand blocks out an ENTIRE SIDE), which is very, very bad. The seller's product description regarding the fans is incredibly misleading. I do not recommend this product to anyone who is having PS4 cooling issues. This product may actually worsen the problem, so stay away from it.

TL;DR:
If you need to cool your PS4, do not buy this stand. It will not help the situation and could actually make it worse! Waste of money, so stay away!

column6: Resident Evil: Revelations 2
column14:
The 360 version is a sloppy port of what is a otherwise not-too-bad game on other consoles. You have to deal with:

- Extreme load times, upwards of 2 minutes.
- Can't install to hard drive which exacerbates already long loading.
- In-game loading drops the frame rate to the point of being unplayable, you have to stand and wait for it to finish for 20-30 seconds.
- Numerous game bugs (textures randomly changing or disappearing, audio dropping out entirely, bad hit detection)
- Very poor controls that don't resemble the tight, responsive control system in Re4/Re5/ReRev regardless of the configuration. The game was clearly designed for a mouse and keyboard first with the console controls as an afterthought.
- Cumbersome aiming: holding any direction while aiming a weapon locks the camera and the direction you are facing, so you have to center the left trigger every single time you shoot.

Capcom did a rush job on porting this to the 360 with little concern about the quality or playability of the result. No patches since the release date have addressed any of these issues. It seems unlikely they'll ever fix it at this point.

About the game itself: For people that liked Resident Evil Revelations, other than sharing some graphical assets this game has nothing to do with that one. It's a sequel in name only with a completely different look and feel. It isn't bad though, and Resident Evil fans will probably want to pick it up.

Given all these issues I'd only recommend getting it for cheap (under $10). Or get it on the PS4 or XBox One where it isn't so broken.

column6: Mega Man Battle Network 3: Blue
column13: The game is solid. One of those must haves!
column14: I decided to pick this game up since I'm collecting the whole BN series and I had previously owned it when it first dropped when I was younger and I loved it! Was very surprised at the price it was going for since it was considerably cheaper than BN1 and BN2, but easily one of the best. The graphics may seem somewhat decent some people, but for its time, you have to admit the graphics were and still are pretty dope (IMO). The amount and type of battle chips in this game are nice and the style changes are pretty cool not to mention the good ol' navi cust which lets you add some pretty nifty extra features to Mega Man. The story was pretty solid to me and if you know Mega Man games. Of course he has to save the world again with the help of his friends and others along the way. Mega Man fans will know what I mean by this statement lol. The longevity of the game is somewhat fair and if you like doing extra areas, missions, etc, it becomes much longer. The bosses and overall battles in this game have been by far the most difficult of any MMBN game that I have played. Those who watch the Mega man series will be disappointed (or please) to know that the games for the most part DO NOT follow the series. With that all said, I honestly recommend picking this up before its price possibly ups as much as BN1 or BN6. This was a really great game when I was younger and it still is. If the game is enjoyed for what it is and not compared in any kind of way to the series or any other Mega Man installations, then you'll definitely love it.

column6: Mortal Kombat X
column13: A balanced and complete modern fighter
column14:
Very cool package that I picked up Prime Day on a complete whim. I haven't played fighting games in something like 10 years and MKX was a great place to start again. There's a staggering amount of content here and the mediocre training mode doesn't really help acclimate you, but I eventually got into a groove and I can now hold my own in the normal difficulty. I personally like fighting with Ferra/Torr and Jason, but, again, so much content here that I haven't even begun to skim the surface.

The fighting games I remember from my teenage years weren't exactly known for groundbreaking story modes, but the underlying tale of MKX is one of the more enjoyable 4-6 hours that I've spent with a video game recently. It's cheesy, sure, but also charming and heartfelt (especially for a game in which you're regularly tearing people in half). Props to the developer.

The statue and packaging are beautiful. Not what I bought it for, but very cool

column6: Dark Messiah: Might & Magic
column13: A Little Known Gem of a Game
column14: I really liked this game. I had never heard of it before, until I did an impromptu search for games by Ubisoft and found it in the list. A quick view of what the game was like on YouTube and I decided to try it. The story is interesting, and teases you all the way to the end. It has challenging puzzles and the gameplay mechanics are easy to master. I'm not a huge fan of 1st person style gameplay, but it worked well in this game and I thoroughly enjoyed it. Since you play as one type of character (mage, warrior, assassin, etc...) you can play the game more than once using a different skill set each time. You can also choose whether to be evil or good, which will change the story as well. If you like Oblivion, Dragon Age or The Witcher, I think you will really enjoy this game as well. There are multi-player online options of play as well, that will further extend your enjoyment of the game.

column6: Power Rangers Super MegaForce - Nintendo 3DS
column14: The game is a semi 2d world with no 3d elements at all.you have 9 chapters with 6 missions each. After you beat a chapter go to achievements an tap the present box, you will unlock all the rangers this way. It took me 4 chapters to figure that out..thats 24 missions due to poor directions. You hack and slash with 3 attacks. charge,light/heavy,and special. The special is not to be confused with the ultimate attack which is only acquired after saving special attack bars. The music is nice especially in the shop. The rangers are fun for any gan but wont be knocking your socks off..that said it never gets old using the mighty mophin ranger or the green rangers sword. The game is fun but is for kids and does have cheesy Victory lines. I personally love power rangers and think this is a major improvement over the garbage of megaforce. I say port this game to console with better visuals and add dlc characters..but then again a 3ds exclusive with double the rangers would also be welcome. Good game to play for any die hard 20+yr old out there wanting a small taste of nostalgia.
